Now at the Macky Gallery: Theresa Yantosca Boulder artist Theresa Yantosca debuts at the Macky Gallery with a collection of large-scale paintings depicting the complexity of human expression. The show runs January 12-February 9 with an artist reception on Friday, January 14 5-7 p.m. The reception is free and open to the public. <p>This collection of new work addresses individual and common identity and draws on a universal understanding of facial expressions, body language and movement. Each painting is an exploration of how expressions of joy, grief, celebration, frustration, happiness, anger spill out of our physical being, coloring our consciousness.</p><p>Theresa Yantosca's visual art includes graphic design and performance installations for organizations such as Moving People Dance Theatre, Flash in the Pan Produkshins and Bao Bao Festival. She is currently performing with Mokomba, a contemporary African dance and drum ensemble.</p> Macky Auditorium 303-492-8423 macky@colorado.edu Arts & Culture-Visual Arts,Macky Auditorium Main Campus Macky Auditorium <li>Everyone</li> Free to the public every Wednesday. This concert by one of the world&#8217;s most renowned Yiddish performers highlights the history of Yiddish behind the &#8220;iron curtain&#8221; in East Germany and asks why would a Communist state be interested in Yiddish at all. The evening&#8217;s repertoire includes some popular favorites like Never Say (Zog nisht keynmol) but also includes some more haunting melodies that made up the canon of East German Yiddish song. CU's Week of Jewish Culture incorporates the theme of Movers: Do You Speak Jewish? this year with authors, scholars and artists from around the world. This annual series is dedicated to the exploration of 3500 years of Jewish culture, including its current, most cutting-edge manifestations! Visit <a title="www.jewishmovers.org" target="_blank" href="www.jewishmovers.org"></a><a title="www.jewishmovers.org" target="_blank" href="http://www.jewishmovers.org/"><a title="www.jewishmovers.org" target="_blank" href="www.jewishmovers.org">www.jewishmovers.org</a></a> for details. In systems that exhibit self-organizing properties, simple objects interact in simple ways to produce complex structures or emergent behaviors. Examples of natural self-organizing systems abound on all scales, from the microscopic to the cosmologic. In biology, nature uses self-organization to great effect. In certain circumstances, cells self-organize into organisms and organisms self-organize into colonies, flocks, or societies. Despite its importance, self-organization is poorly understood.<br /><br />In this talk, he will provide recent advances in self-organizing systems research, with a concentration on mathematical models and theoretical tools used to aid in understanding self-organizing systems, and present related experimental work from the fields of molecular biology and robotics. And why, despite Godzilla’s destructiveness, do we still love him? Where does Hello Kitty come into this picture and why has she been so important in talking about popular culture and national identity? “From Godzilla to Hello Kitty” will explore the deeper meanings behind two globally famous cultural icons—Godzilla and Hello Kitty—that speak to us about postwar Japan, trauma, and the still unresolved issue of war responsibility. Professor Norihiro Kato (Waseda University) is one of Japan’s most important and controversial Japanese literary and cultural critics. He has published more than thirty books on topics that encompass history, film and visual culture, cultural studies, economics, and political science. Recently he published a widely read and cited op-ed piece in the New York Times expanding his critical engagement beyond Japan. Professor David Shneer will present the life story of Jaldati and her daughter, Jalda Rebling, who picked up where her mother left off, and suggest what it says about Jewish life in Europe, in the immediate aftermath of the Holocaust and today. The show runs January 12-February 9 with an artist reception on Friday, January 14 5-7 p.m. The reception is free and open to the public. <p>This collection of new work addresses individual and common identity and draws on a universal understanding of facial expressions, body language and movement. Each painting is an exploration of how expressions of joy, grief, celebration, frustration, happiness, anger spill out of our physical being, coloring our consciousness.</p><p>Theresa Yantosca's visual art includes graphic design and performance installations for organizations such as Moving People Dance Theatre, Flash in the Pan Produkshins and Bao Bao Festival. Study Abroad Progams 303-492-7741 studyabr@colorado.edu International Education-Study Abroad Main Campus Center for Community <li>Students</li> N 1/19/2011 05:30 PM 1/19/2011 06:30 PM One Time 2249 Willard Loop Drive Boulder CO Foreign Objects, sound/music performance by Australian duo <div>"Clocked Out Duo are ready and willing to expand your musical horizons." &#8211;Brett McCallon, Splendid E-zine (USA)</div> <div> <br /> </div> <div>Piano and percussion become sculptural installation as mundane objects spring to life in Clocked Out Duo's most recent offering &#8220;Foreign Objects.&#8221; Brisbane-based Erik Griswold and Vanessa Tomlinson use bowls, bottles, tiles, recycled materials, water, prepared piano and toy instruments to create an extended super-instrument.&#160;</div> <div> <br /> </div> <div>Approaching the performance like an action painter, Tomlinson whips two nylon ropes in a chaotic dance, striking an array of plates, bowls and other detritus. Accompanied by Griswold&#8217;s prepared piano, the result is &#8220;a kaleidoscopic exploration of timbre, texture and rhythmic interplay.&#8221; &#8211;Resonate Magazine.</div> <div> <br /> </div> <div> <br /> </div> <div>Clocked Out Duo use prepared piano, percussion, toy instruments and found objects to create "a detailed orchestration of percussive and resonant sounds" (Chris Reid, Realtime85). Their work embraces a range of influences from experimental composition (John Cage, Terry Riley, Morton Feldman) to free improvisation (George Lewis) to traditional Chinese percussion. In their playful and adventurous work, Clocked Out Duo create links between disparate styles and artistic communities.&#160;</div> <div> <br /> </div> <div>www.clockedout.org</div> <div>http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=g5N3FFbjxhU</div> <div>http://www.youtube.com/theclockedout#p/u/23/-DV84tN-Yvc&#160;</div> 303-735-4577 cuatlas@colorado.edu Arts & Culture-Performing Arts,Arts & Culture-Performing Arts Main Campus ATLAS Center N 1/19/2011 07:30 PM 1/19/2011 09:00 PM Series 1125 18TH STREET Boulder CO http://www.colorado.edu/campusmap/map.html?bldg=ATLS Kafka's Commentary on Czechoslovakian Soccer with Professor Robert Adler-Peckerar <div> <em>"...snad ted footbal vubec prestane... [perhaps now, soccer is really over]"</em> </div> <div> <br /> </div> <div>With these enigmatic words, famed soccer fan Franz Kafka ended a 1923 postcard to his brother-in-law after reading a series of articles railing against the fastest growing sport in the world. Join Robert Adler Peckerar, assistant professor of Jewish Literature and Culture at CU-Boulder, for an interactive evening that examines the phenomenon of Jewish soccer in central and eastern Europe at the start of the last century &#8211; its controversies, politics, and importance in understanding the birth of a new European Jewish culture.</div> <div> <br /> </div> <div>Presented in conjunction with the community-wide series, Czech Point Denver (<a href="http://www.czechpointdenver.com" target="_blank">www.czechpointdenver.com</a>)</div> <div>Location: SOBO 151 151 S. N 1/21/2011 10:00 AM 1/21/2011 05:00 PM Series 1085 18TH STREET Boulder CO Highlights of the Collection: Charles Partridge Adams Paintings The CU Art Museum presents two paintings by the noted Colorado landscape painter Charles Partridge Adams, including a never-before-shown, large-scale painting of Rocky Mountain scenery near Estes Park, titled Sunrise on the Mountains, circa 1920, recently conserved by the CU Art Museum, and gifted to the museum&#8217;s permanent collection by the artist&#8217;s sons. The exhibition will also feature the more intimate Untitled (Mountain Landscape), circa 1920, which likely depicts Moraine Park.&#160;&#160; Born in Massachusetts, Charles Partridge Adams moved to Denver at the age of 18 and eventually became perhaps the most prolific and well known of the turn-of-the-century Colorado painters. Receiving artistic encouragement from Helen Henderson Chain, herself a pupil of George Inness, Adams shied away from the grandiose style employed by his contemporaries, preferring to accentuate the emotive in his landscapes and ushering in a long tradition of modernist landscape painting in the Rocky Mountain region. Jennifer Conrad jennifer.conrad@colorado.edu Arts & Culture-Visual Arts,Arts and Sciences,CU Art Museum,Exhibits & Gallery Shows-Temporary / Visiting Exhibits Main Campus Visual Arts Complex CU Art Museum <li>Everyone</li> Free and open to the public Image credit: Charles Partridge Adams, American (1858-1942) 'Sunrise on the Mountains at the Head of Moraine Park, Near Estes Park, Colorado,' c. 1920s oil on canvas 40 x 60 inches Gift of Philip, Albert and Charles P. Adams Jr., sons of the late Charles Partridge Adams, CU Art Museum, University of Colorado at Boulder, 86.1825 Photo: J Wells © Regents of the University of Colorado / CU Art Museum N 1/21/2011 10:00 AM 1/21/2011 05:00 PM Series 1085 18TH STREET Boulder CO Highlights of the Collection: Selections from the Andy Warhol Photographic Legacy Program Gift <div>In 2008, the CU Art Museum received 156 photographs by Andy Warhol as a gift of the Andy Warhol Foundation for the Visual Arts as part of the Andy Warhol Photographic Legacy Program. The CU Art Museum will premier 112 of the gifted photographs which include Polaroids and gelatin silver prints featuring celebrities such as Martha Graham, Pel&#233;, and John Denver, as well as portraits of patrons, friends, and anonymous models. Included among the gifted gelatin silver prints are also landscapes and interior settings, both rural and urban, which reveal an aesthetic of the banal as well as the transcendental. The photographs provide valuable insight into the artist&#8217;s blurring of the distinction between &#8220;life&#8221; and &#8220;art&#8221; and his construct of &#8220;the celebrity.&#8221;&#160; The exhibition includes 80 Polaroids and 32 gelatin silver prints taken by the Pop-Art master. </div> <div>&#160;</div> <div> <u>Concurrent Exhibition:</u>&#160;&#160; <em>Warhol In Colorado</em>, an exhibition featuring screen prints, photographs, record album covers and other works by Andy Warhol, will be on view at The University of Denver&#8217;s Victoria H. Myhren Gallery from January 20 to March 13, 2011. Also included are 55 Polaroids and silver prints gifted to the university by the Andy Warhol Photographic Legacy Program in 2008.&#160; Details at <a href="http://myhrengallery.wordpress.com/our-namesake/">www.du.edu/art/myhrengallery </a><br /></div> <div> <br /> </div> <div>&#160;</div> <div>&#160;</div> Jennifer Conrad jennifer.conrad@colorado.edu Arts & Culture-Visual Arts,Arts and Sciences,CU Art Museum,Exhibits & Gallery Shows-Temporary / Visiting Exhibits Main Campus Visual Arts Complex CU Art Museum <li>Everyone</li> Free and open to the public Image credit: Andy Warhol, American (1928-1987) 'Pele,' 1977 Polacolor Type 108 4 ¼ x 3 3/8 inches Gift of The Andy Warhol Foundation for the Visual Arts, Inc., The Andy Warhol Photographic Legacy Program, CU Art Museum, University of Colorado at Boulder, 2008.2.39 © The Andy Warhol Foundation for the Visual Arts N 1/21/2011 10:00 AM 1/21/2011 05:00 PM Series 1085 18TH STREET Boulder CO Stages: 50 Years of Theatre at CU Celebrating the golden anniversary of the theater department through colorful photographs, costumes and props. Final Round The College of Music at the University of Colorado at Boulder is excited to announce its first competition dedicated specifically to collaborative music-making: <em>So You Think You Can Collaborate?</em><br /><br /> The most significant and innovative feature of the competition is that participants must consider the audience to be part of the collaborative process. This means that their presentation must not only include a high-level collaborative performance, but must include some component that engages the audience &#8211; be it speaking, technology, dance, as a few examples &#8211; with the goal of enhancing the audience&#8217;s appreciation, enjoyment and understanding of the musical performance. Much time has been spent discussing the classical music industry&#8217;s need to revitalize its audiences, and this is a competition that will reward performers who do just that.<br /><br /> The winners will be determined by an audience vote &#8211; you're the judge of which performers were most engaging!<br /><br /> Special thanks to the College of Music&#8217;s performing departments, who are providing the funds for the award money for this inaugural competition. All College of Music students are eligible to participate.<br /><br /> The <em>So You Think You Can Collaborate? </em>competition is taking place as part of an international day celebrating collaboration, an effort spearheaded by the Music Teachers National Association as part of its Year of Collaborative Music 2010-2011. N 1/24/2011 10:00 AM 1/24/2011 05:00 PM Series 1085 18TH STREET Boulder CO Highlights of the Collection: Charles Partridge Adams Paintings The CU Art Museum presents two paintings by the noted Colorado landscape painter Charles Partridge Adams, including a never-before-shown, large-scale painting of Rocky Mountain scenery near Estes Park, titled Sunrise on the Mountains, circa 1920, recently conserved by the CU Art Museum, and gifted to the museum&#8217;s permanent collection by the artist&#8217;s sons. The exhibition will also feature the more intimate Untitled (Mountain Landscape), circa 1920, which likely depicts Moraine Park.&#160;&#160; Born in Massachusetts, Charles Partridge Adams moved to Denver at the age of 18 and eventually became perhaps the most prolific and well known of the turn-of-the-century Colorado painters. Receiving artistic encouragement from Helen Henderson Chain, herself a pupil of George Inness, Adams shied away from the grandiose style employed by his contemporaries, preferring to accentuate the emotive in his landscapes and ushering in a long tradition of modernist landscape painting in the Rocky Mountain region. N 1/26/2011 10:00 AM 1/26/2011 05:00 PM Series 1085 18TH STREET Boulder CO Highlights of the Collection: Charles Partridge Adams Paintings The CU Art Museum presents two paintings by the noted Colorado landscape painter Charles Partridge Adams, including a never-before-shown, large-scale painting of Rocky Mountain scenery near Estes Park, titled Sunrise on the Mountains, circa 1920, recently conserved by the CU Art Museum, and gifted to the museum&#8217;s permanent collection by the artist&#8217;s sons. The exhibition will also feature the more intimate Untitled (Mountain Landscape), circa 1920, which likely depicts Moraine Park.&#160;&#160; Born in Massachusetts, Charles Partridge Adams moved to Denver at the age of 18 and eventually became perhaps the most prolific and well known of the turn-of-the-century Colorado painters. Receiving artistic encouragement from Helen Henderson Chain, herself a pupil of George Inness, Adams shied away from the grandiose style employed by his contemporaries, preferring to accentuate the emotive in his landscapes and ushering in a long tradition of modernist landscape painting in the Rocky Mountain region. Jennifer Conrad jennifer.conrad@colorado.edu Arts & Culture-Visual Arts,Arts and Sciences,CU Art Museum,Exhibits & Gallery Shows-Temporary / Visiting Exhibits Main Campus Visual Arts Complex CU Art Museum <li>Everyone</li> Free and open to the public Image credit: Charles Partridge Adams, American (1858-1942) 'Sunrise on the Mountains at the Head of Moraine Park, Near Estes Park, Colorado,' c. 1920s oil on canvas 40 x 60 inches Gift of Philip, Albert and Charles P. Adams Jr., sons of the late Charles Partridge Adams, CU Art Museum, University of Colorado at Boulder, 86.1825 Photo: J Wells © Regents of the University of Colorado / CU Art Museum N 1/26/2011 10:00 AM 1/26/2011 05:00 PM Series 1085 18TH STREET Boulder CO Highlights of the Collection: Selections from the Andy Warhol Photographic Legacy Program Gift <div>In 2008, the CU Art Museum received 156 photographs by Andy Warhol as a gift of the Andy Warhol Foundation for the Visual Arts as part of the Andy Warhol Photographic Legacy Program. The CU Art Museum will premier 112 of the gifted photographs which include Polaroids and gelatin silver prints featuring celebrities such as Martha Graham, Pel&#233;, and John Denver, as well as portraits of patrons, friends, and anonymous models. Included among the gifted gelatin silver prints are also landscapes and interior settings, both rural and urban, which reveal an aesthetic of the banal as well as the transcendental. The photographs provide valuable insight into the artist&#8217;s blurring of the distinction between &#8220;life&#8221; and &#8220;art&#8221; and his construct of &#8220;the celebrity.&#8221;&#160; The exhibition includes 80 Polaroids and 32 gelatin silver prints taken by the Pop-Art master. </div> <div>&#160;</div> <div> <u>Concurrent Exhibition:</u>&#160;&#160; <em>Warhol In Colorado</em>, an exhibition featuring screen prints, photographs, record album covers and other works by Andy Warhol, will be on view at The University of Denver&#8217;s Victoria H. Myhren Gallery from January 20 to March 13, 2011. Today's employment challenge is to anticipate and prepare for change before it happens. If you are going through a job transition, retiring but don't really want to, want to start a new business or not sure what to do, join us for an in-depth career "reset". <p> Now in its 6th year, our blended approach has assisted 100's of participants through coaching, self-discovery and technology. <br /> * Develop career branding, resumes and marketing tools <br /> * Learn technology tricks and techniques to improve your results <br /> * Discover online assessments, career resources and research tools <br /> * Develop an action plan &amp; long-term career management strategies <br /> * Expand your network </p><p>"Conducted in a very open and comfortable atmosphere, the course gave me courage to honestly assess what I wanted to do with my life and take a realistic look at my talents, weaknesses, priorities, motivations and values." <br />"It set me in a new thought process regarding the work I do for the first time... N 1/27/2011 10:00 AM 1/27/2011 05:00 PM Series 1085 18TH STREET Boulder CO Highlights of the Collection: Charles Partridge Adams Paintings The CU Art Museum presents two paintings by the noted Colorado landscape painter Charles Partridge Adams, including a never-before-shown, large-scale painting of Rocky Mountain scenery near Estes Park, titled Sunrise on the Mountains, circa 1920, recently conserved by the CU Art Museum, and gifted to the museum&#8217;s permanent collection by the artist&#8217;s sons. The exhibition will also feature the more intimate Untitled (Mountain Landscape), circa 1920, which likely depicts Moraine Park.&#160;&#160; Born in Massachusetts, Charles Partridge Adams moved to Denver at the age of 18 and eventually became perhaps the most prolific and well known of the turn-of-the-century Colorado painters. Receiving artistic encouragement from Helen Henderson Chain, herself a pupil of George Inness, Adams shied away from the grandiose style employed by his contemporaries, preferring to accentuate the emotive in his landscapes and ushering in a long tradition of modernist landscape painting in the Rocky Mountain region. Jennifer Conrad jennifer.conrad@colorado.edu Arts & Culture-Visual Arts,Arts and Sciences,CU Art Museum,Exhibits & Gallery Shows-Temporary / Visiting Exhibits Main Campus Visual Arts Complex CU Art Museum <li>Everyone</li> Free and open to the public Image credit: Charles Partridge Adams, American (1858-1942) 'Sunrise on the Mountains at the Head of Moraine Park, Near Estes Park, Colorado,' c. 1920s oil on canvas 40 x 60 inches Gift of Philip, Albert and Charles P. Adams Jr., sons of the late Charles Partridge Adams, CU Art Museum, University of Colorado at Boulder, 86.1825 Photo: J Wells © Regents of the University of Colorado / CU Art Museum N 1/27/2011 10:00 AM 1/27/2011 05:00 PM Series 1085 18TH STREET Boulder CO Highlights of the Collection: Selections from the Andy Warhol Photographic Legacy Program Gift <div>In 2008, the CU Art Museum received 156 photographs by Andy Warhol as a gift of the Andy Warhol Foundation for the Visual Arts as part of the Andy Warhol Photographic Legacy Program. The CU Art Museum will premier 112 of the gifted photographs which include Polaroids and gelatin silver prints featuring celebrities such as Martha Graham, Pel&#233;, and John Denver, as well as portraits of patrons, friends, and anonymous models. Included among the gifted gelatin silver prints are also landscapes and interior settings, both rural and urban, which reveal an aesthetic of the banal as well as the transcendental. The photographs provide valuable insight into the artist&#8217;s blurring of the distinction between &#8220;life&#8221; and &#8220;art&#8221; and his construct of &#8220;the celebrity.&#8221;&#160; The exhibition includes 80 Polaroids and 32 gelatin silver prints taken by the Pop-Art master. </div> <div>&#160;</div> <div> <u>Concurrent Exhibition:</u>&#160;&#160; <em>Warhol In Colorado</em>, an exhibition featuring screen prints, photographs, record album covers and other works by Andy Warhol, will be on view at The University of Denver&#8217;s Victoria H. Myhren Gallery from January 20 to March 13, 2011. N 1/27/2011 06:00 PM 1/27/2011 08:00 PM One Time 2249 Willard Loop Drive Boulder CO "The People are Dancing Again" Charles Wilkinson Book Release <div>The Center of the American West celebrates the release of Charles Wilkinson's recently published book, "The People Are Dancing Again: The History of the Siletz Tribe of Western Oregon." In the book, Wilkinson, co-founder of the Center of the American West and CU-Boulder's Moses Lasky Professor of Law, brings to life the history of the Siletz people, a history that in many ways reflects the history of all Indian tribes. This account is rich in Indian voices and grounded in extensive research that includes oral tradition and personal interviews.</div> <div>&#160;</div> <div>Books will be for sale at this event, which is free and open to the public. N 1/28/2011 11:00 AM 1/28/2011 01:00 PM Series 1595 PLEASANT ST Boulder CO http://www.colorado.edu/campusmap/map.html?bldg=MCKY Oasis Community Circle <div>Oasis invites you to share mat&#233; and join our community circle. On most Fridays, we use the traditional South American beverage mat&#233; to create a simple social ritual and develop dynamic community and conversation. This ritual is used to cultivate an inclusive community of mutual support, to help us foster rich relationships, and to uplift our spirits. Please join us as we look to create a dynamic community on the CU campus dedicated to sobriety, connection, and friendship. </div> <div>&#160;</div> <div>To learn more about the Oasis Community at CU-Boulder, please visit our <a href="http://www.colorado.edu/sacs/counseling/oasis/index.html" target="_blank">website</a>.</div> Matthew Tomatz 303-492-1397 matthew.tomatz@colorado.edu Student Affairs,Student Events,Student Organizations and Clubs,Student Organizations and Clubs-Special Interest Main Campus Center for Community 448 <li>Students</li><li>Faculty</li><li>Staff</li><li>Graduate Students</li> N 1/28/2011 03:00 PM 1/28/2011 04:00 PM Series 2249 Willard Loop Drive Boulder CO INTERNATIONAL COFFEE HOUR, FRIDAYS, 4-5:30 PM, UMC GRILL ACROSS FROM BABY DOE'S Join us each Friday when classes are in session, from 4 - 5:30 pm, across from Baby Doe's in the UMC Grill.&#160; The conversations are great and refreshments are free!&#160; CU students, faculty and staff are all welcome to join approximately 200 people who attend each week! N 1/28/2011 07:30 PM 1/28/2011 10:00 PM One Time 1020 18th Street Boulder CO http://www.colorado.edu/campusmap/map.html?bldg=MUS Nathan Wheeler's "Sept. 6th," multimedia performance <p style="margin: 0.0px 0.0px 0.0px 0.0px; font: 12.0px Helvetica">September Sixth is Boulder artist Nathan Wheeler's musical/theatrical memoir and response to the devastating Four Mile Canyon fire. <br /><br /> The hour-long performance will be presented two evenings: 8 p.m. Friday-Saturday, Jan. 28-29 in the ATLAS Black Box, downstairs, lower-level B2, CU-Boulder. <br /><br /> CU music graduate Wheeler explains, &#8220;September Sixth is my reaction to the Four Mile Canyon Fire which started on September 6th, 2010. The fire burned our home to the ground&#8211;home to my grandfather who built the house, my parents, younger brother and me. My grandfather built the house in the 1960s. My mother and her family were raised there. And so were my brother and I. We moved in when I was 6."<br /><br /> The piece uses a combination of found art, sound sculpture, dance, music and video to explore the fire, its aftermath and effect on Wheeler's life. A variety of photos of the site taken by collaborators Michael Theodore, Jeff Ruane, Mark McCoin and as well as Wheeler will be projected on the wall of the ATLAS lobby.<br /><br /> &#8220;The performance will feature myself on electronics, harmonium, voice, guitar and found objects. I will also do live video and dance. Janet Feder (a regular performer with the Boulder Laptop Orchestra) will play prepared guitar and found objects. Mark McCoin will also play found objects. CU masters graduate Curtis Broome will play drums. Luke Iwabuchi and Skye Hughes of CU's dance department will provide movement.<br /><br /> &#8220;The work will mirror the emotions I went through because of the fire&#8211;surprise, anguish and suffering, then acceptance, and finally&#8211;peace, joy and reverence."<br /><br /> Musical genres include a cappella, ambient, drone, noise, post-hardcore rock, and electronica. Live video accompanies most of the performance. Dance includes contact improvisation.<br /><br /> The show is free and open to the public. <br /><strong>Reservations are recommended. </strong>Reserve your seat here: http://septsixth.eventbrite.com/<br /><br /> Note: The show will have moments of loud sustained sounds&#8211;earplugs will be provided at the door.</p> <p style="margin: 0.0px 0.0px 0.0px 0.0px; font: 12.0px Helvetica"> </p> 303-735-4577 cuatlas@colorado.edu Arts & Culture-Performing Arts,Arts & Culture-Performing Arts Main Campus ATLAS Center N 1/28/2011 08:00 PM 1/28/2011 09:00 PM Series 1125 18TH STREET Boulder CO http://www.colorado.edu/campusmap/map.html?bldg=ATLS Laser Outkast Enjoy some of Outkast's greatest hits set to Fiske lasers and special effects! N 1/29/2011 12:00 PM 1/29/2011 04:00 PM Series 1085 18TH STREET Boulder CO Highlights of the Collection: Charles Partridge Adams Paintings The CU Art Museum presents two paintings by the noted Colorado landscape painter Charles Partridge Adams, including a never-before-shown, large-scale painting of Rocky Mountain scenery near Estes Park, titled Sunrise on the Mountains, circa 1920, recently conserved by the CU Art Museum, and gifted to the museum&#8217;s permanent collection by the artist&#8217;s sons. The exhibition will also feature the more intimate Untitled (Mountain Landscape), circa 1920, which likely depicts Moraine Park.&#160;&#160; Born in Massachusetts, Charles Partridge Adams moved to Denver at the age of 18 and eventually became perhaps the most prolific and well known of the turn-of-the-century Colorado painters. Receiving artistic encouragement from Helen Henderson Chain, herself a pupil of George Inness, Adams shied away from the grandiose style employed by his contemporaries, preferring to accentuate the emotive in his landscapes and ushering in a long tradition of modernist landscape painting in the Rocky Mountain region. Jennifer Conrad jennifer.conrad@colorado.edu Arts & Culture-Visual Arts,Arts and Sciences,CU Art Museum,Exhibits & Gallery Shows-Temporary / Visiting Exhibits Main Campus Visual Arts Complex CU Art Museum <li>Everyone</li> Free and open to the public Image credit: Charles Partridge Adams, American (1858-1942) 'Sunrise on the Mountains at the Head of Moraine Park, Near Estes Park, Colorado,' c. 1920s oil on canvas 40 x 60 inches Gift of Philip, Albert and Charles P. Adams Jr., sons of the late Charles Partridge Adams, CU Art Museum, University of Colorado at Boulder, 86.1825 Photo: J Wells © Regents of the University of Colorado / CU Art Museum N 1/29/2011 12:00 PM 1/29/2011 04:00 PM Series 1085 18TH STREET Boulder CO Highlights of the Collection: Selections from the Andy Warhol Photographic Legacy Program Gift <div>In 2008, the CU Art Museum received 156 photographs by Andy Warhol as a gift of the Andy Warhol Foundation for the Visual Arts as part of the Andy Warhol Photographic Legacy Program. The CU Art Museum will premier 112 of the gifted photographs which include Polaroids and gelatin silver prints featuring celebrities such as Martha Graham, Pel&#233;, and John Denver, as well as portraits of patrons, friends, and anonymous models. Included among the gifted gelatin silver prints are also landscapes and interior settings, both rural and urban, which reveal an aesthetic of the banal as well as the transcendental. The photographs provide valuable insight into the artist&#8217;s blurring of the distinction between &#8220;life&#8221; and &#8220;art&#8221; and his construct of &#8220;the celebrity.&#8221;&#160; The exhibition includes 80 Polaroids and 32 gelatin silver prints taken by the Pop-Art master. </div> <div>&#160;</div> <div> <u>Concurrent Exhibition:</u>&#160;&#160; <em>Warhol In Colorado</em>, an exhibition featuring screen prints, photographs, record album covers and other works by Andy Warhol, will be on view at The University of Denver&#8217;s Victoria H. Myhren Gallery from January 20 to March 13, 2011. Also included are 55 Polaroids and silver prints gifted to the university by the Andy Warhol Photographic Legacy Program in 2008.&#160; Details at <a href="http://myhrengallery.wordpress.com/our-namesake/">www.du.edu/art/myhrengallery </a><br /></div> <div> <br /> </div> <div>&#160;</div> <div>&#160;</div> Jennifer Conrad jennifer.conrad@colorado.edu Arts & Culture-Visual Arts,Arts and Sciences,CU Art Museum,Exhibits & Gallery Shows-Temporary / Visiting Exhibits Main Campus Visual Arts Complex CU Art Museum <li>Everyone</li> Free and open to the public Image credit: Andy Warhol, American (1928-1987) 'Pele,' 1977 Polacolor Type 108 4 ¼ x 3 3/8 inches Gift of The Andy Warhol Foundation for the Visual Arts, Inc., The Andy Warhol Photographic Legacy Program, CU Art Museum, University of Colorado at Boulder, 2008.2.39 © The Andy Warhol Foundation for the Visual Arts N 1/29/2011 12:00 PM 1/29/2011 04:00 PM Series 1085 18TH STREET Boulder CO The 2011 Faculty Exhibition <div>Featuring the work of 22 faculty artists from the Department of Art and Art History at the University of Colorado at Boulder, the CU Art Museum&#8217;s 2011 Faculty Exhibition will include works in numerous media, including video and sound installation, painting, photography, ceramics, digital arts, printmaking, sculpture, and mixed-media installations. N 1/29/2011 07:30 PM 1/29/2011 09:30 PM One Time 1020 18th Street Boulder CO http://www.colorado.edu/campusmap/map.html?bldg=MUS The Pillowman <div id="id_4d2f3f0f12d319067760188" class="text_exposed_root text_exposed">The University of Colorado Boulder Theatre and Dance Proudly Presents:<br /><br /> THE PILLOWMAN, by Martin McDonagh<br /> Jan 26-30<br /> Directed by LoriLee Wallace<br /><span class="text_exposed_hide">...</span><span class="text_exposed_show"><br /> University of Colorado, Department of Theatre and Dance is proud to present &#8220;The Pillowman&#8221; by Martin McDonagh.<br /><br /> Truth or Fiction? In this spellbinding black comedy, the classic who-done-it plot is turned on its (severed) head when a writer of gruesome murder stories is arrested.<br /><br /> The play&#8217;s protagonist is an arrogant man whose 400 short pieces of fiction — only one published — might be read as a how-to guide of &#8220;101 ways to skewer a 5-year-old.&#8221; McDonagh feels life, much like storytelling, is a puzzle without solution and that there are no happy endings. He weaves complex thoughts and gory acts into a gripping, very entertaining theatre experience. <br /><br /> January 26-30<br /> Presented in the Loft Theatre<br /><br /> Box Office: 303.492.8181<br /> Or tix Online: <a href="http://www.colorado.edu/theatredance/" rel="nofollow" target="_blank">www.colorado.edu/theatreda<wbr><span class="word_break"></span>nce/</wbr></a><br /><br /> Map to the Building: <a href="http://www.colorado.edu/campusmap/map.html?bldg=THTR" rel="nofollow" target="_blank">www.colorado.edu/campusmap<wbr><span class="word_break"></span>/map.html?bldg=THTR</wbr></a></span></div> Arts & Culture,Arts & Culture-Performing Arts,Arts & Culture-Student Productions,Arts and Sciences-Theatre and Dance,Student Events,Student Events-Culture Nights <li>Everyone</li> N 1/29/2011 07:30 PM 1/29/2011 09:30 PM Series Nathan Wheeler's "Sept. 6th," multimedia performance <p style="margin: 0.0px 0.0px 0.0px 0.0px; font: 12.0px Helvetica">September Sixth is Boulder artist Nathan Wheeler's musical/theatrical memoir and response to the devastating Four Mile Canyon fire. <br /><br /> The hour-long performance will be presented two evenings: 8 p.m. Friday-Saturday, Jan. 28-29 in the ATLAS Black Box, downstairs, lower-level B2, CU-Boulder. <br /><br /> CU music graduate Wheeler explains, &#8220;September Sixth is my reaction to the Four Mile Canyon Fire which started on September 6th, 2010. The fire burned our home to the ground&#8211;home to my grandfather who built the house, my parents, younger brother and me. My grandfather built the house in the 1960s. My mother and her family were raised there. And so were my brother and I. We moved in when I was 6."<br /><br /> The piece uses a combination of found art, sound sculpture, dance, music and video to explore the fire, its aftermath and effect on Wheeler's life. A variety of photos of the site taken by collaborators Michael Theodore, Jeff Ruane, Mark McCoin and as well as Wheeler will be projected on the wall of the ATLAS lobby.<br /><br /> &#8220;The performance will feature myself on electronics, harmonium, voice, guitar and found objects. I will also do live video and dance. Janet Feder (a regular performer with the Boulder Laptop Orchestra) will play prepared guitar and found objects. Mark McCoin will also play found objects. CU masters graduate Curtis Broome will play drums. Luke Iwabuchi and Skye Hughes of CU's dance department will provide movement.<br /><br /> &#8220;The work will mirror the emotions I went through because of the fire&#8211;surprise, anguish and suffering, then acceptance, and finally&#8211;peace, joy and reverence."<br /><br /> Musical genres include a cappella, ambient, drone, noise, post-hardcore rock, and electronica. Live video accompanies most of the performance. Dance includes contact improvisation.<br /><br /> The show is free and open to the public. <br /><strong>Reservations are recommended. </strong>Reserve your seat here: http://septsixth.eventbrite.com/<br /><br /> Note: The show will have moments of loud sustained sounds&#8211;earplugs will be provided at the door.</p> <p style="margin: 0.0px 0.0px 0.0px 0.0px; font: 12.0px Helvetica"> </p> 303-735-4577 cuatlas@colorado.edu Arts & Culture-Performing Arts,Arts & Culture-Performing Arts Main Campus ATLAS Center N 1/29/2011 08:00 PM 1/29/2011 09:00 PM Series 1125 18TH STREET Boulder CO http://www.colorado.edu/campusmap/map.html?bldg=ATLS The Pillowman <div id="id_4d2f3f0f12d319067760188" class="text_exposed_root text_exposed">The University of Colorado Boulder Theatre and Dance Proudly Presents:<br /><br /> THE PILLOWMAN, by Martin McDonagh<br /> Jan 26-30<br /> Directed by LoriLee Wallace<br /><span class="text_exposed_hide">...</span><span class="text_exposed_show"><br /> University of Colorado, Department of Theatre and Dance is proud to present &#8220;The Pillowman&#8221; by Martin McDonagh.<br /><br /> Truth or Fiction? N 1/31/2011 10:00 AM 1/31/2011 05:00 PM Series 1085 18TH STREET Boulder CO Highlights of the Collection: Charles Partridge Adams Paintings The CU Art Museum presents two paintings by the noted Colorado landscape painter Charles Partridge Adams, including a never-before-shown, large-scale painting of Rocky Mountain scenery near Estes Park, titled Sunrise on the Mountains, circa 1920, recently conserved by the CU Art Museum, and gifted to the museum&#8217;s permanent collection by the artist&#8217;s sons. The exhibition will also feature the more intimate Untitled (Mountain Landscape), circa 1920, which likely depicts Moraine Park.&#160;&#160; Born in Massachusetts, Charles Partridge Adams moved to Denver at the age of 18 and eventually became perhaps the most prolific and well known of the turn-of-the-century Colorado painters. Receiving artistic encouragement from Helen Henderson Chain, herself a pupil of George Inness, Adams shied away from the grandiose style employed by his contemporaries, preferring to accentuate the emotive in his landscapes and ushering in a long tradition of modernist landscape painting in the Rocky Mountain region. Adams Jr., sons of the late Charles Partridge Adams, CU Art Museum, University of Colorado at Boulder, 86.1825 Photo: J Wells © Regents of the University of Colorado / CU Art Museum N 1/31/2011 10:00 AM 1/31/2011 05:00 PM Series 1085 18TH STREET Boulder CO Highlights of the Collection: Selections from the Andy Warhol Photographic Legacy Program Gift <div>In 2008, the CU Art Museum received 156 photographs by Andy Warhol as a gift of the Andy Warhol Foundation for the Visual Arts as part of the Andy Warhol Photographic Legacy Program. The CU Art Museum will premier 112 of the gifted photographs which include Polaroids and gelatin silver prints featuring celebrities such as Martha Graham, Pel&#233;, and John Denver, as well as portraits of patrons, friends, and anonymous models. Included among the gifted gelatin silver prints are also landscapes and interior settings, both rural and urban, which reveal an aesthetic of the banal as well as the transcendental. The photographs provide valuable insight into the artist&#8217;s blurring of the distinction between &#8220;life&#8221; and &#8220;art&#8221; and his construct of &#8220;the celebrity.&#8221;&#160; The exhibition includes 80 Polaroids and 32 gelatin silver prints taken by the Pop-Art master. </div> <div>&#160;</div> <div> <u>Concurrent Exhibition:</u>&#160;&#160; <em>Warhol In Colorado</em>, an exhibition featuring screen prints, photographs, record album covers and other works by Andy Warhol, will be on view at The University of Denver&#8217;s Victoria H. Myhren Gallery from January 20 to March 13, 2011. Also included are 55 Polaroids and silver prints gifted to the university by the Andy Warhol Photographic Legacy Program in 2008.&#160; Details at <a href="http://myhrengallery.wordpress.com/our-namesake/">www.du.edu/art/myhrengallery </a><br /></div> <div> <br /> </div> <div>&#160;</div> <div>&#160;</div> Jennifer Conrad jennifer.conrad@colorado.edu Arts & Culture-Visual Arts,Arts and Sciences,CU Art Museum,Exhibits & Gallery Shows-Temporary / Visiting Exhibits Main Campus Visual Arts Complex CU Art Museum <li>Everyone</li> Free and open to the public Image credit: Andy Warhol, American (1928-1987) 'Pele,' 1977 Polacolor Type 108 4 ¼ x 3 3/8 inches Gift of The Andy Warhol Foundation for the Visual Arts, Inc., The Andy Warhol Photographic Legacy Program, CU Art Museum, University of Colorado at Boulder, 2008.2.39 © The Andy Warhol Foundation for the Visual Arts N 1/31/2011 10:00 AM 1/31/2011 05:00 PM Series 1085 18TH STREET Boulder CO Stages: 50 Years of Theatre at CU Celebrating the golden anniversary of the theater department through colorful photographs, costumes and props. N 1/31/2011 10:00 AM 1/31/2011 05:00 PM Series 1600 PLEASANT ST Boulder CO http://www.colorado.edu/campusmap/map.html?bldg=MAIN The 2011 Faculty Exhibition <div>Featuring the work of 22 faculty artists from the Department of Art and Art History at the University of Colorado at Boulder, the CU Art Museum&#8217;s 2011 Faculty Exhibition will include works in numerous media, including video and sound installation, painting, photography, ceramics, digital arts, printmaking, sculpture, and mixed-media installations. The Yes Men attempt to raise awareness of public issues through large scale hoaxes which often include impersonation of corporate and government representatives and the creation of mock websites and press releases. They have produced two films documenting their work: The Yes Men and The Yes Men Fix the World, which premiered at the Sundance Film Festival. N 2/01/2011 07:30 PM 2/01/2011 09:30 PM One Time 1020 18th Street Boulder CO http://www.colorado.edu/campusmap/map.html?bldg=MUS Now at the Macky Gallery: Theresa Yantosca Boulder artist Theresa Yantosca debuts at the Macky Gallery with a collection of large-scale paintings depicting the complexity of human expression. The show runs January 12-February 9 with an artist reception on Friday, January 14 5-7 p.m. The reception is free and open to the public. <p>This collection of new work addresses individual and common identity and draws on a universal understanding of facial expressions, body language and movement. Each painting is an exploration of how expressions of joy, grief, celebration, frustration, happiness, anger spill out of our physical being, coloring our consciousness.</p><p>Theresa Yantosca's visual art includes graphic design and performance installations for organizations such as Moving People Dance Theatre, Flash in the Pan Produkshins and Bao Bao Festival. She is currently performing with Mokomba, a contemporary African dance and drum ensemble.</p> Macky Auditorium 303-492-8423 macky@colorado.edu Arts & Culture-Visual Arts,Macky Auditorium Main Campus Macky Auditorium <li>Everyone</li> Free to the public every Wednesday. N 2/02/2011 10:00 AM 2/02/2011 05:00 PM Series 1085 18TH STREET Boulder CO Highlights of the Collection: Charles Partridge Adams Paintings The CU Art Museum presents two paintings by the noted Colorado landscape painter Charles Partridge Adams, including a never-before-shown, large-scale painting of Rocky Mountain scenery near Estes Park, titled Sunrise on the Mountains, circa 1920, recently conserved by the CU Art Museum, and gifted to the museum&#8217;s permanent collection by the artist&#8217;s sons. The exhibition will also feature the more intimate Untitled (Mountain Landscape), circa 1920, which likely depicts Moraine Park.&#160;&#160; Born in Massachusetts, Charles Partridge Adams moved to Denver at the age of 18 and eventually became perhaps the most prolific and well known of the turn-of-the-century Colorado painters. Receiving artistic encouragement from Helen Henderson Chain, herself a pupil of George Inness, Adams shied away from the grandiose style employed by his contemporaries, preferring to accentuate the emotive in his landscapes and ushering in a long tradition of modernist landscape painting in the Rocky Mountain region. The CU Art Museum will premier 112 of the gifted photographs which include Polaroids and gelatin silver prints featuring celebrities such as Martha Graham, Pel&#233;, and John Denver, as well as portraits of patrons, friends, and anonymous models. Included among the gifted gelatin silver prints are also landscapes and interior settings, both rural and urban, which reveal an aesthetic of the banal as well as the transcendental. The photographs provide valuable insight into the artist&#8217;s blurring of the distinction between &#8220;life&#8221; and &#8220;art&#8221; and his construct of &#8220;the celebrity.&#8221;&#160; The exhibition includes 80 Polaroids and 32 gelatin silver prints taken by the Pop-Art master. </div> <div>&#160;</div> <div> <u>Concurrent Exhibition:</u>&#160;&#160; <em>Warhol In Colorado</em>, an exhibition featuring screen prints, photographs, record album covers and other works by Andy Warhol, will be on view at The University of Denver&#8217;s Victoria H. N 2/04/2011 10:00 AM 2/04/2011 05:00 PM Series 1085 18TH STREET Boulder CO Highlights of the Collection: Charles Partridge Adams Paintings The CU Art Museum presents two paintings by the noted Colorado landscape painter Charles Partridge Adams, including a never-before-shown, large-scale painting of Rocky Mountain scenery near Estes Park, titled Sunrise on the Mountains, circa 1920, recently conserved by the CU Art Museum, and gifted to the museum&#8217;s permanent collection by the artist&#8217;s sons. The exhibition will also feature the more intimate Untitled (Mountain Landscape), circa 1920, which likely depicts Moraine Park.&#160;&#160; Born in Massachusetts, Charles Partridge Adams moved to Denver at the age of 18 and eventually became perhaps the most prolific and well known of the turn-of-the-century Colorado painters. Receiving artistic encouragement from Helen Henderson Chain, herself a pupil of George Inness, Adams shied away from the grandiose style employed by his contemporaries, preferring to accentuate the emotive in his landscapes and ushering in a long tradition of modernist landscape painting in the Rocky Mountain region. The CU Art Museum will premier 112 of the gifted photographs which include Polaroids and gelatin silver prints featuring celebrities such as Martha Graham, Pel&#233;, and John Denver, as well as portraits of patrons, friends, and anonymous models. Included among the gifted gelatin silver prints are also landscapes and interior settings, both rural and urban, which reveal an aesthetic of the banal as well as the transcendental. The photographs provide valuable insight into the artist&#8217;s blurring of the distinction between &#8220;life&#8221; and &#8220;art&#8221; and his construct of &#8220;the celebrity.&#8221;&#160; The exhibition includes 80 Polaroids and 32 gelatin silver prints taken by the Pop-Art master. </div> <div>&#160;</div> <div> <u>Concurrent Exhibition:</u>&#160;&#160; <em>Warhol In Colorado</em>, an exhibition featuring screen prints, photographs, record album covers and other works by Andy Warhol, will be on view at The University of Denver&#8217;s Victoria H. N 2/07/2011 10:00 AM 2/07/2011 05:00 PM Series 1085 18TH STREET Boulder CO Highlights of the Collection: Charles Partridge Adams Paintings The CU Art Museum presents two paintings by the noted Colorado landscape painter Charles Partridge Adams, including a never-before-shown, large-scale painting of Rocky Mountain scenery near Estes Park, titled Sunrise on the Mountains, circa 1920, recently conserved by the CU Art Museum, and gifted to the museum&#8217;s permanent collection by the artist&#8217;s sons. The exhibition will also feature the more intimate Untitled (Mountain Landscape), circa 1920, which likely depicts Moraine Park.&#160;&#160; Born in Massachusetts, Charles Partridge Adams moved to Denver at the age of 18 and eventually became perhaps the most prolific and well known of the turn-of-the-century Colorado painters. Receiving artistic encouragement from Helen Henderson Chain, herself a pupil of George Inness, Adams shied away from the grandiose style employed by his contemporaries, preferring to accentuate the emotive in his landscapes and ushering in a long tradition of modernist landscape painting in the Rocky Mountain region. Adams Jr., sons of the late Charles Partridge Adams, CU Art Museum, University of Colorado at Boulder, 86.1825 Photo: J Wells © Regents of the University of Colorado / CU Art Museum N 2/07/2011 10:00 AM 2/07/2011 05:00 PM Series 1085 18TH STREET Boulder CO Highlights of the Collection: Selections from the Andy Warhol Photographic Legacy Program Gift <div>In 2008, the CU Art Museum received 156 photographs by Andy Warhol as a gift of the Andy Warhol Foundation for the Visual Arts as part of the Andy Warhol Photographic Legacy Program. The CU Art Museum will premier 112 of the gifted photographs which include Polaroids and gelatin silver prints featuring celebrities such as Martha Graham, Pel&#233;, and John Denver, as well as portraits of patrons, friends, and anonymous models. Included among the gifted gelatin silver prints are also landscapes and interior settings, both rural and urban, which reveal an aesthetic of the banal as well as the transcendental. The photographs provide valuable insight into the artist&#8217;s blurring of the distinction between &#8220;life&#8221; and &#8220;art&#8221; and his construct of &#8220;the celebrity.&#8221;&#160; The exhibition includes 80 Polaroids and 32 gelatin silver prints taken by the Pop-Art master. </div> <div>&#160;</div> <div> <u>Concurrent Exhibition:</u>&#160;&#160; <em>Warhol In Colorado</em>, an exhibition featuring screen prints, photographs, record album covers and other works by Andy Warhol, will be on view at The University of Denver&#8217;s Victoria H. Myhren Gallery from January 20 to March 13, 2011. Also included are 55 Polaroids and silver prints gifted to the university by the Andy Warhol Photographic Legacy Program in 2008.&#160; Details at <a href="http://myhrengallery.wordpress.com/our-namesake/">www.du.edu/art/myhrengallery </a><br /></div> <div> <br /> </div> <div>&#160;</div> <div>&#160;</div> Jennifer Conrad jennifer.conrad@colorado.edu Arts & Culture-Visual Arts,Arts and Sciences,CU Art Museum,Exhibits & Gallery Shows-Temporary / Visiting Exhibits Main Campus Visual Arts Complex CU Art Museum <li>Everyone</li> Free and open to the public Image credit: Andy Warhol, American (1928-1987) 'Pele,' 1977 Polacolor Type 108 4 ¼ x 3 3/8 inches Gift of The Andy Warhol Foundation for the Visual Arts, Inc., The Andy Warhol Photographic Legacy Program, CU Art Museum, University of Colorado at Boulder, 2008.2.39 © The Andy Warhol Foundation for the Visual Arts N 2/07/2011 10:00 AM 2/07/2011 05:00 PM Series 1085 18TH STREET Boulder CO Stages: 50 Years of Theatre at CU Celebrating the golden anniversary of the theater department through colorful photographs, costumes and props. N 2/08/2011 07:30 PM 2/08/2011 09:30 PM One Time 1595 PLEASANT ST Boulder CO http://www.colorado.edu/campusmap/map.html?bldg=MCKY Now at the Macky Gallery: Theresa Yantosca Boulder artist Theresa Yantosca debuts at the Macky Gallery with a collection of large-scale paintings depicting the complexity of human expression. The show runs January 12-February 9 with an artist reception on Friday, January 14 5-7 p.m. The reception is free and open to the public. <p>This collection of new work addresses individual and common identity and draws on a universal understanding of facial expressions, body language and movement. Each painting is an exploration of how expressions of joy, grief, celebration, frustration, happiness, anger spill out of our physical being, coloring our consciousness.</p><p>Theresa Yantosca's visual art includes graphic design and performance installations for organizations such as Moving People Dance Theatre, Flash in the Pan Produkshins and Bao Bao Festival. She is currently performing with Mokomba, a contemporary African dance and drum ensemble.</p> Macky Auditorium 303-492-8423 macky@colorado.edu Arts & Culture-Visual Arts,Macky Auditorium Main Campus Macky Auditorium <li>Everyone</li> Free to the public every Wednesday. The gallery is also open evenings of performances to ticketed patrons. N 2/10/2011 10:00 AM 2/10/2011 05:00 PM Series 1085 18TH STREET Boulder CO Highlights of the Collection: Charles Partridge Adams Paintings The CU Art Museum presents two paintings by the noted Colorado landscape painter Charles Partridge Adams, including a never-before-shown, large-scale painting of Rocky Mountain scenery near Estes Park, titled Sunrise on the Mountains, circa 1920, recently conserved by the CU Art Museum, and gifted to the museum&#8217;s permanent collection by the artist&#8217;s sons. The exhibition will also feature the more intimate Untitled (Mountain Landscape), circa 1920, which likely depicts Moraine Park.&#160;&#160; Born in Massachusetts, Charles Partridge Adams moved to Denver at the age of 18 and eventually became perhaps the most prolific and well known of the turn-of-the-century Colorado painters. Receiving artistic encouragement from Helen Henderson Chain, herself a pupil of George Inness, Adams shied away from the grandiose style employed by his contemporaries, preferring to accentuate the emotive in his landscapes and ushering in a long tradition of modernist landscape painting in the Rocky Mountain region. Jennifer Conrad jennifer.conrad@colorado.edu Arts & Culture-Visual Arts,Arts and Sciences,CU Art Museum,Exhibits & Gallery Shows-Temporary / Visiting Exhibits Main Campus Visual Arts Complex CU Art Museum <li>Everyone</li> Free and open to the public Image credit: Charles Partridge Adams, American (1858-1942) 'Sunrise on the Mountains at the Head of Moraine Park, Near Estes Park, Colorado,' c. 1920s oil on canvas 40 x 60 inches Gift of Philip, Albert and Charles P. Adams Jr., sons of the late Charles Partridge Adams, CU Art Museum, University of Colorado at Boulder, 86.1825 Photo: J Wells © Regents of the University of Colorado / CU Art Museum N 2/10/2011 10:00 AM 2/10/2011 05:00 PM Series 1085 18TH STREET Boulder CO Highlights of the Collection: Selections from the Andy Warhol Photographic Legacy Program Gift <div>In 2008, the CU Art Museum received 156 photographs by Andy Warhol as a gift of the Andy Warhol Foundation for the Visual Arts as part of the Andy Warhol Photographic Legacy Program. The CU Art Museum will premier 112 of the gifted photographs which include Polaroids and gelatin silver prints featuring celebrities such as Martha Graham, Pel&#233;, and John Denver, as well as portraits of patrons, friends, and anonymous models. Included among the gifted gelatin silver prints are also landscapes and interior settings, both rural and urban, which reveal an aesthetic of the banal as well as the transcendental. The photographs provide valuable insight into the artist&#8217;s blurring of the distinction between &#8220;life&#8221; and &#8220;art&#8221; and his construct of &#8220;the celebrity.&#8221;&#160; The exhibition includes 80 Polaroids and 32 gelatin silver prints taken by the Pop-Art master. </div> <div>&#160;</div> <div> <u>Concurrent Exhibition:</u>&#160;&#160; <em>Warhol In Colorado</em>, an exhibition featuring screen prints, photographs, record album covers and other works by Andy Warhol, will be on view at The University of Denver&#8217;s Victoria H. Myhren Gallery from January 20 to March 13, 2011. Also included are 55 Polaroids and silver prints gifted to the university by the Andy Warhol Photographic Legacy Program in 2008.&#160; Details at <a href="http://myhrengallery.wordpress.com/our-namesake/">www.du.edu/art/myhrengallery </a><br /></div> <div> <br /> </div> <div>&#160;</div> <div>&#160;</div> Jennifer Conrad jennifer.conrad@colorado.edu Arts & Culture-Visual Arts,Arts and Sciences,CU Art Museum,Exhibits & Gallery Shows-Temporary / Visiting Exhibits Main Campus Visual Arts Complex CU Art Museum <li>Everyone</li> Free and open to the public Image credit: Andy Warhol, American (1928-1987) 'Pele,' 1977 Polacolor Type 108 4 ¼ x 3 3/8 inches Gift of The Andy Warhol Foundation for the Visual Arts, Inc., The Andy Warhol Photographic Legacy Program, CU Art Museum, University of Colorado at Boulder, 2008.2.39 © The Andy Warhol Foundation for the Visual Arts N 2/10/2011 10:00 AM 2/10/2011 05:00 PM Series 1085 18TH STREET Boulder CO Stages: 50 Years of Theatre at CU Celebrating the golden anniversary of the theater department through colorful photographs, costumes and props. For more information, please call our main office at 303-492-5002 or check our website at fiske.colorado.edu N 2/11/2011 10:45 PM 2/11/2011 11:45 PM One Time 408 UCB CO 303-492-5002 http://fiske.colorado.edu CU on the Weekend - Zombie Renaissance Professor of English Stephen Jones' class won&#8217;t prepare you for the zombie apocalypse because we&#8217;re already infested with the undead! They&#8217;re everywhere &#8211; books, comics, songs, movies, and all the way down to the warning alerts you get on your home computer. This class will take you back to Gilgamesh and Tibet to the world&#8217;s first zombies, and then explore religion within Haiti until you have an uncomfortably intimate understanding of the living dead, know their taxonomy, what characterizes them as a species, and where &#8211; if anywhere &#8211; to draw the line between us and them. Just as importantly, you&#8217;ll begin to suspect how the zombie is constantly being used and recycled to express or address society&#8217;s many anxieties. It&#8217;s no accident that Night of the Living Dead was a hit when it was nor is it a coincidence that 28 Days Later premiered when it did. As for the Zombie Renaissance, there&#8217;s no better time to study it than now. N 2/12/2011 12:00 PM 2/12/2011 04:00 PM Series 1085 18TH STREET Boulder CO Highlights of the Collection: Charles Partridge Adams Paintings The CU Art Museum presents two paintings by the noted Colorado landscape painter Charles Partridge Adams, including a never-before-shown, large-scale painting of Rocky Mountain scenery near Estes Park, titled Sunrise on the Mountains, circa 1920, recently conserved by the CU Art Museum, and gifted to the museum&#8217;s permanent collection by the artist&#8217;s sons. The exhibition will also feature the more intimate Untitled (Mountain Landscape), circa 1920, which likely depicts Moraine Park.&#160;&#160; Born in Massachusetts, Charles Partridge Adams moved to Denver at the age of 18 and eventually became perhaps the most prolific and well known of the turn-of-the-century Colorado painters. Receiving artistic encouragement from Helen Henderson Chain, herself a pupil of George Inness, Adams shied away from the grandiose style employed by his contemporaries, preferring to accentuate the emotive in his landscapes and ushering in a long tradition of modernist landscape painting in the Rocky Mountain region. The CU Art Museum will premier 112 of the gifted photographs which include Polaroids and gelatin silver prints featuring celebrities such as Martha Graham, Pel&#233;, and John Denver, as well as portraits of patrons, friends, and anonymous models. Included among the gifted gelatin silver prints are also landscapes and interior settings, both rural and urban, which reveal an aesthetic of the banal as well as the transcendental. The CU Art Museum will premier 112 of the gifted photographs which include Polaroids and gelatin silver prints featuring celebrities such as Martha Graham, Pel&#233;, and John Denver, as well as portraits of patrons, friends, and anonymous models. Included among the gifted gelatin silver prints are also landscapes and interior settings, both rural and urban, which reveal an aesthetic of the banal as well as the transcendental. N 2/16/2011 10:00 AM 2/16/2011 05:00 PM Series 1085 18TH STREET Boulder CO Highlights of the Collection: Charles Partridge Adams Paintings The CU Art Museum presents two paintings by the noted Colorado landscape painter Charles Partridge Adams, including a never-before-shown, large-scale painting of Rocky Mountain scenery near Estes Park, titled Sunrise on the Mountains, circa 1920, recently conserved by the CU Art Museum, and gifted to the museum&#8217;s permanent collection by the artist&#8217;s sons. The exhibition will also feature the more intimate Untitled (Mountain Landscape), circa 1920, which likely depicts Moraine Park.&#160;&#160; Born in Massachusetts, Charles Partridge Adams moved to Denver at the age of 18 and eventually became perhaps the most prolific and well known of the turn-of-the-century Colorado painters. Receiving artistic encouragement from Helen Henderson Chain, herself a pupil of George Inness, Adams shied away from the grandiose style employed by his contemporaries, preferring to accentuate the emotive in his landscapes and ushering in a long tradition of modernist landscape painting in the Rocky Mountain region. N 2/18/2011 10:00 AM 2/18/2011 05:00 PM Series 1085 18TH STREET Boulder CO Highlights of the Collection: Charles Partridge Adams Paintings The CU Art Museum presents two paintings by the noted Colorado landscape painter Charles Partridge Adams, including a never-before-shown, large-scale painting of Rocky Mountain scenery near Estes Park, titled Sunrise on the Mountains, circa 1920, recently conserved by the CU Art Museum, and gifted to the museum&#8217;s permanent collection by the artist&#8217;s sons. The exhibition will also feature the more intimate Untitled (Mountain Landscape), circa 1920, which likely depicts Moraine Park.&#160;&#160; Born in Massachusetts, Charles Partridge Adams moved to Denver at the age of 18 and eventually became perhaps the most prolific and well known of the turn-of-the-century Colorado painters. Receiving artistic encouragement from Helen Henderson Chain, herself a pupil of George Inness, Adams shied away from the grandiose style employed by his contemporaries, preferring to accentuate the emotive in his landscapes and ushering in a long tradition of modernist landscape painting in the Rocky Mountain region. Adams Jr., sons of the late Charles Partridge Adams, CU Art Museum, University of Colorado at Boulder, 86.1825 Photo: J Wells © Regents of the University of Colorado / CU Art Museum N 2/18/2011 10:00 AM 2/18/2011 05:00 PM Series 1085 18TH STREET Boulder CO Highlights of the Collection: Selections from the Andy Warhol Photographic Legacy Program Gift <div>In 2008, the CU Art Museum received 156 photographs by Andy Warhol as a gift of the Andy Warhol Foundation for the Visual Arts as part of the Andy Warhol Photographic Legacy Program. The CU Art Museum will premier 112 of the gifted photographs which include Polaroids and gelatin silver prints featuring celebrities such as Martha Graham, Pel&#233;, and John Denver, as well as portraits of patrons, friends, and anonymous models. Included among the gifted gelatin silver prints are also landscapes and interior settings, both rural and urban, which reveal an aesthetic of the banal as well as the transcendental. The photographs provide valuable insight into the artist&#8217;s blurring of the distinction between &#8220;life&#8221; and &#8220;art&#8221; and his construct of &#8220;the celebrity.&#8221;&#160; The exhibition includes 80 Polaroids and 32 gelatin silver prints taken by the Pop-Art master. </div> <div>&#160;</div> <div> <u>Concurrent Exhibition:</u>&#160;&#160; <em>Warhol In Colorado</em>, an exhibition featuring screen prints, photographs, record album covers and other works by Andy Warhol, will be on view at The University of Denver&#8217;s Victoria H. Myhren Gallery from January 20 to March 13, 2011. Also included are 55 Polaroids and silver prints gifted to the university by the Andy Warhol Photographic Legacy Program in 2008.&#160; Details at <a href="http://myhrengallery.wordpress.com/our-namesake/">www.du.edu/art/myhrengallery </a><br /></div> <div> <br /> </div> <div>&#160;</div> <div>&#160;</div> Jennifer Conrad jennifer.conrad@colorado.edu Arts & Culture-Visual Arts,Arts and Sciences,CU Art Museum,Exhibits & Gallery Shows-Temporary / Visiting Exhibits Main Campus Visual Arts Complex CU Art Museum <li>Everyone</li> Free and open to the public Image credit: Andy Warhol, American (1928-1987) 'Pele,' 1977 Polacolor Type 108 4 ¼ x 3 3/8 inches Gift of The Andy Warhol Foundation for the Visual Arts, Inc., The Andy Warhol Photographic Legacy Program, CU Art Museum, University of Colorado at Boulder, 2008.2.39 © The Andy Warhol Foundation for the Visual Arts N 2/18/2011 10:00 AM 2/18/2011 05:00 PM Series 1085 18TH STREET Boulder CO Stages: 50 Years of Theatre at CU Celebrating the golden anniversary of the theater department through colorful photographs, costumes and props. In essence, this class will focus on the highlights of Hohlfelder&#8217;s career of archaeological and historical discovery. N 2/20/2011 02:00 PM 2/20/2011 03:30 PM One Time 1020 18th Street Boulder CO http://www.colorado.edu/campusmap/map.html?bldg=MUS Guest Recital: Esther Park, piano Pianist Esther Park has performed as a soloist with orchestras and in recitals across the United States as well as in Korea, China, Canada, Russia, Ireland, Spain, Poland, Italy and Israel. Ms. Park has appeared as soloist with many orchestras such as Corpus Christi Symphony, Filharmonia Pomorska, Poland, Orchestra Filarmonica, Romania, Shanghai Philharmonic, China, the American Academy of Conducting Orchestra at Aspen, Shreveport Symphony, the Juilliard Symphony, and the New Jersey Symphony.<br /><div>&#160;<br /></div><div>Ms. Park is the winner of the 2004 Gina Bachauer Piano Competition at the Juilliard School. She is the winner of the Juilliard concerto competition, the 52nd Kosciusko International Piano Competition, New Jersey Young Artists Audition, the Van Cliburn-TCU Institute Young Artist Competition, Corpus Christi International Competition, top prizes at the 3rd China Shanghai International Piano Competition, 6th Paderewski International Piano Competition, the National Chopin Competition, Hilton Head International Competition, the 14th New Orleans International Piano Competition, and is the recipient of the President Clinton&#8217;s Prodigy Award.</div><div>&#160;</div><div>Born in Pusan, Korea in 1984, Ms. Park began to play in public soon after her first piano lessons at the age of four. Ms. Park moved to the United States in 1995, after being accepted to the Juilliard School&#8217;s Pre-College division. Ms. Park has since received her Bachelor&#8217;s degree and Master&#8217;s degree from the Juilliard School, studying with Yoheved Kaplinsky. She has performed in master classes of Arie Vardi, Richard Goode, Leon Fleisher, Jerome Lowenthal, Joseph Kalichstein, Andrew Litton, Joachin Achuccaro, and Karl Ulrich Schnabel. </div><div>&#160;</div><div>PROGRAM:</div><div>Bach - <em>English Suite in g minor, no. 3</em></div><div>Haydn - <em>Sonata in c minor</em></div><div>Liszt - <em>Rigoletto Paraphrase</em></div><div>Chopin - <em>Variations in E Major</em>; <em>Prelude in c-sharp minor</em>, Op. 45; <em>Barcarolle</em>, Op. 60; and <em>Scherzo no. 3 </em><br /></div> CU Presents Box Office 303-492-8008 musictix@colorado.edu Arts & Culture-Performing Arts,College & School Events,College of Music,College of Music-Guest Recitals,College of Music-Keyboard Main Campus Imig Music Grusin Music Hall <li>Everyone</li> Free and open to the public. N 2/21/2011 10:00 AM 2/21/2011 05:00 PM Series 1085 18TH STREET Boulder CO Highlights of the Collection: Charles Partridge Adams Paintings The CU Art Museum presents two paintings by the noted Colorado landscape painter Charles Partridge Adams, including a never-before-shown, large-scale painting of Rocky Mountain scenery near Estes Park, titled Sunrise on the Mountains, circa 1920, recently conserved by the CU Art Museum, and gifted to the museum&#8217;s permanent collection by the artist&#8217;s sons. The exhibition will also feature the more intimate Untitled (Mountain Landscape), circa 1920, which likely depicts Moraine Park.&#160;&#160; Born in Massachusetts, Charles Partridge Adams moved to Denver at the age of 18 and eventually became perhaps the most prolific and well known of the turn-of-the-century Colorado painters. Receiving artistic encouragement from Helen Henderson Chain, herself a pupil of George Inness, Adams shied away from the grandiose style employed by his contemporaries, preferring to accentuate the emotive in his landscapes and ushering in a long tradition of modernist landscape painting in the Rocky Mountain region. Adams Jr., sons of the late Charles Partridge Adams, CU Art Museum, University of Colorado at Boulder, 86.1825 Photo: J Wells © Regents of the University of Colorado / CU Art Museum N 2/21/2011 10:00 AM 2/21/2011 05:00 PM Series 1085 18TH STREET Boulder CO Highlights of the Collection: Selections from the Andy Warhol Photographic Legacy Program Gift <div>In 2008, the CU Art Museum received 156 photographs by Andy Warhol as a gift of the Andy Warhol Foundation for the Visual Arts as part of the Andy Warhol Photographic Legacy Program. The CU Art Museum will premier 112 of the gifted photographs which include Polaroids and gelatin silver prints featuring celebrities such as Martha Graham, Pel&#233;, and John Denver, as well as portraits of patrons, friends, and anonymous models. Included among the gifted gelatin silver prints are also landscapes and interior settings, both rural and urban, which reveal an aesthetic of the banal as well as the transcendental. The photographs provide valuable insight into the artist&#8217;s blurring of the distinction between &#8220;life&#8221; and &#8220;art&#8221; and his construct of &#8220;the celebrity.&#8221;&#160; The exhibition includes 80 Polaroids and 32 gelatin silver prints taken by the Pop-Art master. </div> <div>&#160;</div> <div> <u>Concurrent Exhibition:</u>&#160;&#160; <em>Warhol In Colorado</em>, an exhibition featuring screen prints, photographs, record album covers and other works by Andy Warhol, will be on view at The University of Denver&#8217;s Victoria H. Myhren Gallery from January 20 to March 13, 2011. N 2/23/2011 10:00 AM 2/23/2011 05:00 PM Series 1085 18TH STREET Boulder CO Highlights of the Collection: Charles Partridge Adams Paintings The CU Art Museum presents two paintings by the noted Colorado landscape painter Charles Partridge Adams, including a never-before-shown, large-scale painting of Rocky Mountain scenery near Estes Park, titled Sunrise on the Mountains, circa 1920, recently conserved by the CU Art Museum, and gifted to the museum&#8217;s permanent collection by the artist&#8217;s sons. The exhibition will also feature the more intimate Untitled (Mountain Landscape), circa 1920, which likely depicts Moraine Park.&#160;&#160; Born in Massachusetts, Charles Partridge Adams moved to Denver at the age of 18 and eventually became perhaps the most prolific and well known of the turn-of-the-century Colorado painters. Receiving artistic encouragement from Helen Henderson Chain, herself a pupil of George Inness, Adams shied away from the grandiose style employed by his contemporaries, preferring to accentuate the emotive in his landscapes and ushering in a long tradition of modernist landscape painting in the Rocky Mountain region. The CU Art Museum will premier 112 of the gifted photographs which include Polaroids and gelatin silver prints featuring celebrities such as Martha Graham, Pel&#233;, and John Denver, as well as portraits of patrons, friends, and anonymous models. Included among the gifted gelatin silver prints are also landscapes and interior settings, both rural and urban, which reveal an aesthetic of the banal as well as the transcendental. The photographs provide valuable insight into the artist&#8217;s blurring of the distinction between &#8220;life&#8221; and &#8220;art&#8221; and his construct of &#8220;the celebrity.&#8221;&#160; The exhibition includes 80 Polaroids and 32 gelatin silver prints taken by the Pop-Art master. </div> <div>&#160;</div> <div> <u>Concurrent Exhibition:</u>&#160;&#160; <em>Warhol In Colorado</em>, an exhibition featuring screen prints, photographs, record album covers and other works by Andy Warhol, will be on view at The University of Denver&#8217;s Victoria H. Racial categories are embedded in our language, and racial differences seem obvious. And yet as a scientific tool for understanding human variation race is a myth. I will argue that &#8220;Human Races are arbitrary categories invented to fit a misunderstanding about how humans evolve.&#8221; I will argue further that when the myth bleeds into our social lives someone always gets hurt. Study Abroad Progams 303-492-7741 studyabr@colorado.edu International Education-Study Abroad Main Campus Center for Community <li>Students</li> N 2/24/2011 04:00 PM 2/24/2011 05:00 PM One Time 2249 Willard Loop Drive Boulder CO CAS Event: "Integrated Action of Counterinsurgency & Rural Economic Development for Stable Afghan" Afghanistan faces enormous challenges due to more than 30 years of war, civil unrest and recurring natural disasters. This rugged, landlocked and mountainous country remains one of the poorest in the world, with more than half the population living below the poverty line. So, what are the alternative solutions to bring this unproductive population in an economic mainstream of the society? Dr. Jha is trying hard to create an innovative model, which can be sustainable and techno-economically feasible and replicable for bringing faster economic development in Afghanistan. He has closely watched Afghan people, their culture, governance, infrastructure and various USAID and other donors programs. For the implementation of USG program and strategy, there is a need to provide capacity building training to Afghan extension personnel's who can learn and disseminate appropriate knowledge, skills and technology in fast pace across the country. The exhibition will also feature the more intimate Untitled (Mountain Landscape), circa 1920, which likely depicts Moraine Park.&#160;&#160; Born in Massachusetts, Charles Partridge Adams moved to Denver at the age of 18 and eventually became perhaps the most prolific and well known of the turn-of-the-century Colorado painters. Receiving artistic encouragement from Helen Henderson Chain, herself a pupil of George Inness, Adams shied away from the grandiose style employed by his contemporaries, preferring to accentuate the emotive in his landscapes and ushering in a long tradition of modernist landscape painting in the Rocky Mountain region. The CU Art Museum will premier 112 of the gifted photographs which include Polaroids and gelatin silver prints featuring celebrities such as Martha Graham, Pel&#233;, and John Denver, as well as portraits of patrons, friends, and anonymous models. N 2/25/2011 10:45 PM 2/25/2011 11:45 PM One Time 408 UCB CO 303-492-5002 http://fiske.colorado.edu Who Causes Third World Underdevelopment? The Western world has reached a level of economic well-being and technological achievement that would have been unimaginable just a century ago. Worldwide, however, most countries remain part of the poverty-stricken Third World or global &#8220;South,&#8221; and almost half of humanity survives on less than $2 per day. Associate Professor Andy Baker will explore a wide range of possible reasons and explanations for why so many countries remain poor, and will do so from a wide range of ideological and disciplinary perspectives. Examples and anecdotes from Latin America, Africa, Middle East, China, India, Russia, and elsewhere will comprise an important part of the discussion, and the course will also consider the impact of charitable giving and foreign aid on development. The CU Art Museum will premier 112 of the gifted photographs which include Polaroids and gelatin silver prints featuring celebrities such as Martha Graham, Pel&#233;, and John Denver, as well as portraits of patrons, friends, and anonymous models. Included among the gifted gelatin silver prints are also landscapes and interior settings, both rural and urban, which reveal an aesthetic of the banal as well as the transcendental. The photographs provide valuable insight into the artist&#8217;s blurring of the distinction between &#8220;life&#8221; and &#8220;art&#8221; and his construct of &#8220;the celebrity.&#8221;&#160; The exhibition includes 80 Polaroids and 32 gelatin silver prints taken by the Pop-Art master. </div> <div>&#160;</div> <div> <u>Concurrent Exhibition:</u>&#160;&#160; <em>Warhol In Colorado</em>, an exhibition featuring screen prints, photographs, record album covers and other works by Andy Warhol, will be on view at The University of Denver&#8217;s Victoria H. N 3/01/2011 10:00 AM 3/01/2011 07:00 PM Series 1085 18TH STREET Boulder CO Highlights of the Collection: Charles Partridge Adams Paintings The CU Art Museum presents two paintings by the noted Colorado landscape painter Charles Partridge Adams, including a never-before-shown, large-scale painting of Rocky Mountain scenery near Estes Park, titled Sunrise on the Mountains, circa 1920, recently conserved by the CU Art Museum, and gifted to the museum&#8217;s permanent collection by the artist&#8217;s sons. The exhibition will also feature the more intimate Untitled (Mountain Landscape), circa 1920, which likely depicts Moraine Park.&#160;&#160; Born in Massachusetts, Charles Partridge Adams moved to Denver at the age of 18 and eventually became perhaps the most prolific and well known of the turn-of-the-century Colorado painters. Receiving artistic encouragement from Helen Henderson Chain, herself a pupil of George Inness, Adams shied away from the grandiose style employed by his contemporaries, preferring to accentuate the emotive in his landscapes and ushering in a long tradition of modernist landscape painting in the Rocky Mountain region. N 3/03/2011 10:00 AM 3/03/2011 05:00 PM Series 1085 18TH STREET Boulder CO Highlights of the Collection: Charles Partridge Adams Paintings The CU Art Museum presents two paintings by the noted Colorado landscape painter Charles Partridge Adams, including a never-before-shown, large-scale painting of Rocky Mountain scenery near Estes Park, titled Sunrise on the Mountains, circa 1920, recently conserved by the CU Art Museum, and gifted to the museum&#8217;s permanent collection by the artist&#8217;s sons. The exhibition will also feature the more intimate Untitled (Mountain Landscape), circa 1920, which likely depicts Moraine Park.&#160;&#160; Born in Massachusetts, Charles Partridge Adams moved to Denver at the age of 18 and eventually became perhaps the most prolific and well known of the turn-of-the-century Colorado painters. Receiving artistic encouragement from Helen Henderson Chain, herself a pupil of George Inness, Adams shied away from the grandiose style employed by his contemporaries, preferring to accentuate the emotive in his landscapes and ushering in a long tradition of modernist landscape painting in the Rocky Mountain region.
