The CU Art Museum will premier 112 of the gifted photographs which include Polaroids and gelatin silver prints featuring celebrities such as Martha Graham, Pel&#233;, and John Denver, as well as portraits of patrons, friends, and anonymous models. Included among the gifted gelatin silver prints are also landscapes and interior settings, both rural and urban, which reveal an aesthetic of the banal as well as the transcendental. The photographs provide valuable insight into the artist&#8217;s blurring of the distinction between &#8220;life&#8221; and &#8220;art&#8221; and his construct of &#8220;the celebrity.&#8221;&#160; The exhibition includes 80 Polaroids and 32 gelatin silver prints taken by the Pop-Art master. </div> <div>&#160;</div> <div> <u>Concurrent Exhibition:</u>&#160;&#160; <em>Warhol In Colorado</em>, an exhibition featuring screen prints, photographs, record album covers and other works by Andy Warhol, will be on view at The University of Denver&#8217;s Victoria H. The CU Art Museum will premier 112 of the gifted photographs which include Polaroids and gelatin silver prints featuring celebrities such as Martha Graham, Pel&#233;, and John Denver, as well as portraits of patrons, friends, and anonymous models. Included among the gifted gelatin silver prints are also landscapes and interior settings, both rural and urban, which reveal an aesthetic of the banal as well as the transcendental. The photographs provide valuable insight into the artist&#8217;s blurring of the distinction between &#8220;life&#8221; and &#8220;art&#8221; and his construct of &#8220;the celebrity.&#8221;&#160; The exhibition includes 80 Polaroids and 32 gelatin silver prints taken by the Pop-Art master. </div> <div>&#160;</div> <div> <u>Concurrent Exhibition:</u>&#160;&#160; <em>Warhol In Colorado</em>, an exhibition featuring screen prints, photographs, record album covers and other works by Andy Warhol, will be on view at The University of Denver&#8217;s Victoria H. Myhren Gallery from January 20 to March 13, 2011. N 3/07/2011 10:00 AM 3/07/2011 05:00 PM Series 1085 18TH STREET Boulder CO Highlights of the Collection: Charles Partridge Adams Paintings The CU Art Museum presents two paintings by the noted Colorado landscape painter Charles Partridge Adams, including a never-before-shown, large-scale painting of Rocky Mountain scenery near Estes Park, titled Sunrise on the Mountains, circa 1920, recently conserved by the CU Art Museum, and gifted to the museum&#8217;s permanent collection by the artist&#8217;s sons. The exhibition will also feature the more intimate Untitled (Mountain Landscape), circa 1920, which likely depicts Moraine Park.&#160;&#160; Born in Massachusetts, Charles Partridge Adams moved to Denver at the age of 18 and eventually became perhaps the most prolific and well known of the turn-of-the-century Colorado painters. Receiving artistic encouragement from Helen Henderson Chain, herself a pupil of George Inness, Adams shied away from the grandiose style employed by his contemporaries, preferring to accentuate the emotive in his landscapes and ushering in a long tradition of modernist landscape painting in the Rocky Mountain region. During their process, they contribute to the mixed pieces separately while continually adapting, transforming, and re-working what the other has previously completed. Their process results in a rich and dynamic work, filled with multiple marks, gestures and techniques, symbols and metaphors the delve into memory and subconscious. The Visiting Artist Program has been a vital component of the Department of Art &amp; Art History since 1972. Each year, 8&#8211;10 nationally recognized artists present diverse ideas and their body of work during their visit to the Boulder campus.</div> <div> <a href="http://events.colorado.edu/default.aspx?type=&amp;view=Summary&amp;category=15-58&amp;starting=8/23/2010&amp;ending=5/31/2011" target="_self"> <font color="#000000"> </font> </a> </div> <div>&#160;</div> <div>See all the events in the Visiting Artist Lecture series <a href="http://events.colorado.edu/default.aspx?type=&amp;view=Summary&amp;category=15-58&amp;starting=8/23/2010&amp;ending=5/31/2011" target="_self">&gt;&gt;</a></div> Valerie Albicker 303 492-2539 albicker@colorado.edu Arts & Culture,Arts & Culture-Lectures/Seminars,Arts & Culture-Visiting Artist Program,Arts & Culture-Visual Arts,Arts and Sciences,College & School Events,Cultural Series,Cultural Series-Arts & Culture Week,Featured Events,Lectures & Seminars,Student Events Main Campus Visual Arts Complex 1B20 <li>Everyone</li> N 3/08/2011 07:00 PM 3/08/2011 08:30 PM One Time 1085 18TH STREET Boulder CO Faculty Tuesdays: Chamber Spring Mix <em>Chamber Spring Mix</em> <br /> <br />Come out for an exciting spring profusion of chamber and improvisatory works performed by the CU faculty including Lina Bahn, Andrew Cooperstock, Michael Dunn, Judith Glyde, John Gunther, David Korevaar, Patrick Mason, Margaret McDonald, Paul Miller, Alexandra Nguyen, and Daniel Silver. N 3/09/2011 10:00 AM 3/09/2011 05:00 PM Series 1085 18TH STREET Boulder CO Highlights of the Collection: Charles Partridge Adams Paintings The CU Art Museum presents two paintings by the noted Colorado landscape painter Charles Partridge Adams, including a never-before-shown, large-scale painting of Rocky Mountain scenery near Estes Park, titled Sunrise on the Mountains, circa 1920, recently conserved by the CU Art Museum, and gifted to the museum&#8217;s permanent collection by the artist&#8217;s sons. The exhibition will also feature the more intimate Untitled (Mountain Landscape), circa 1920, which likely depicts Moraine Park.&#160;&#160; Born in Massachusetts, Charles Partridge Adams moved to Denver at the age of 18 and eventually became perhaps the most prolific and well known of the turn-of-the-century Colorado painters. Receiving artistic encouragement from Helen Henderson Chain, herself a pupil of George Inness, Adams shied away from the grandiose style employed by his contemporaries, preferring to accentuate the emotive in his landscapes and ushering in a long tradition of modernist landscape painting in the Rocky Mountain region. Adams Jr., sons of the late Charles Partridge Adams, CU Art Museum, University of Colorado at Boulder, 86.1825 Photo: J Wells © Regents of the University of Colorado / CU Art Museum N 3/09/2011 10:00 AM 3/09/2011 05:00 PM Series 1085 18TH STREET Boulder CO Highlights of the Collection: Selections from the Andy Warhol Photographic Legacy Program Gift <div>In 2008, the CU Art Museum received 156 photographs by Andy Warhol as a gift of the Andy Warhol Foundation for the Visual Arts as part of the Andy Warhol Photographic Legacy Program. The CU Art Museum will premier 112 of the gifted photographs which include Polaroids and gelatin silver prints featuring celebrities such as Martha Graham, Pel&#233;, and John Denver, as well as portraits of patrons, friends, and anonymous models. Included among the gifted gelatin silver prints are also landscapes and interior settings, both rural and urban, which reveal an aesthetic of the banal as well as the transcendental. The photographs provide valuable insight into the artist&#8217;s blurring of the distinction between &#8220;life&#8221; and &#8220;art&#8221; and his construct of &#8220;the celebrity.&#8221;&#160; The exhibition includes 80 Polaroids and 32 gelatin silver prints taken by the Pop-Art master. </div> <div>&#160;</div> <div> <u>Concurrent Exhibition:</u>&#160;&#160; <em>Warhol In Colorado</em>, an exhibition featuring screen prints, photographs, record album covers and other works by Andy Warhol, will be on view at The University of Denver&#8217;s Victoria H. Myhren Gallery from January 20 to March 13, 2011. Susannah draws the attention of several men at a church square dance, including a travelling preacher. Jealous wives begin to gossip. The community struggles to uphold societal and religious expectations, setting a tragic chain of events in motion. Lush, tuneful Appalachian music including "Ain't It a Pretty Night" colors this 1955&#160;version of the apocryphal tale of Susannah and the Elders. Carlisle Floyd's first major opera, it is the second most performed in the American repertoire (after Gershwin's&#160;Porgy and Bess). </div><div>&#160;</div><div>You are welcome to bring your lunch and water to the Brown Bag Preview, but please avoid bringing coffee, tea, and soda into the Music Theatre.&#160; <br /></div> CU Presents Box Office 303-492-8008 musictix@colorado.edu Arts & Culture-Performing Arts,College & School Events,College of Music,College of Music-CU Opera,College of Music-CU Presents,College of Music-Voice Main Campus Imig Music Music Theatre <li>Everyone</li> Free and open to the public. ($) <div>In the Tennessee town of New Hope Valley, a young woman learns that beauty can bear a terrible cost. N 3/12/2011 12:00 PM 3/12/2011 04:00 PM Series 1085 18TH STREET Boulder CO Highlights of the Collection: Charles Partridge Adams Paintings The CU Art Museum presents two paintings by the noted Colorado landscape painter Charles Partridge Adams, including a never-before-shown, large-scale painting of Rocky Mountain scenery near Estes Park, titled Sunrise on the Mountains, circa 1920, recently conserved by the CU Art Museum, and gifted to the museum&#8217;s permanent collection by the artist&#8217;s sons. The exhibition will also feature the more intimate Untitled (Mountain Landscape), circa 1920, which likely depicts Moraine Park.&#160;&#160; Born in Massachusetts, Charles Partridge Adams moved to Denver at the age of 18 and eventually became perhaps the most prolific and well known of the turn-of-the-century Colorado painters. Receiving artistic encouragement from Helen Henderson Chain, herself a pupil of George Inness, Adams shied away from the grandiose style employed by his contemporaries, preferring to accentuate the emotive in his landscapes and ushering in a long tradition of modernist landscape painting in the Rocky Mountain region. Jennifer Conrad jennifer.conrad@colorado.edu Arts & Culture-Visual Arts,Arts and Sciences,CU Art Museum,Exhibits & Gallery Shows-Temporary / Visiting Exhibits Main Campus Visual Arts Complex CU Art Museum <li>Everyone</li> Free and open to the public Image credit: Charles Partridge Adams, American (1858-1942) 'Sunrise on the Mountains at the Head of Moraine Park, Near Estes Park, Colorado,' c. 1920s oil on canvas 40 x 60 inches Gift of Philip, Albert and Charles P. Adams Jr., sons of the late Charles Partridge Adams, CU Art Museum, University of Colorado at Boulder, 86.1825 Photo: J Wells © Regents of the University of Colorado / CU Art Museum N 3/12/2011 12:00 PM 3/12/2011 04:00 PM Series 1085 18TH STREET Boulder CO Highlights of the Collection: Selections from the Andy Warhol Photographic Legacy Program Gift <div>In 2008, the CU Art Museum received 156 photographs by Andy Warhol as a gift of the Andy Warhol Foundation for the Visual Arts as part of the Andy Warhol Photographic Legacy Program. The CU Art Museum will premier 112 of the gifted photographs which include Polaroids and gelatin silver prints featuring celebrities such as Martha Graham, Pel&#233;, and John Denver, as well as portraits of patrons, friends, and anonymous models. Included among the gifted gelatin silver prints are also landscapes and interior settings, both rural and urban, which reveal an aesthetic of the banal as well as the transcendental. The photographs provide valuable insight into the artist&#8217;s blurring of the distinction between &#8220;life&#8221; and &#8220;art&#8221; and his construct of &#8220;the celebrity.&#8221;&#160; The exhibition includes 80 Polaroids and 32 gelatin silver prints taken by the Pop-Art master. </div> <div>&#160;</div> <div> <u>Concurrent Exhibition:</u>&#160;&#160; <em>Warhol In Colorado</em>, an exhibition featuring screen prints, photographs, record album covers and other works by Andy Warhol, will be on view at The University of Denver&#8217;s Victoria H. Myhren Gallery from January 20 to March 13, 2011. Also included are 55 Polaroids and silver prints gifted to the university by the Andy Warhol Photographic Legacy Program in 2008.&#160; Details at <a href="http://myhrengallery.wordpress.com/our-namesake/">www.du.edu/art/myhrengallery </a><br /></div> <div> <br /> </div> <div>&#160;</div> <div>&#160;</div> Jennifer Conrad jennifer.conrad@colorado.edu Arts & Culture-Visual Arts,Arts and Sciences,CU Art Museum,Exhibits & Gallery Shows-Temporary / Visiting Exhibits Main Campus Visual Arts Complex CU Art Museum <li>Everyone</li> Free and open to the public Image credit: Andy Warhol, American (1928-1987) 'Pele,' 1977 Polacolor Type 108 4 ¼ x 3 3/8 inches Gift of The Andy Warhol Foundation for the Visual Arts, Inc., The Andy Warhol Photographic Legacy Program, CU Art Museum, University of Colorado at Boulder, 2008.2.39 © The Andy Warhol Foundation for the Visual Arts N 3/12/2011 12:00 PM 3/12/2011 04:00 PM Series 1085 18TH STREET Boulder CO CU on the Weekend - Picasso and World War II - A Question of Patriotism Associate Professor Albert Alhadeff will discuss a fascinating aspect of Pablo Picasso&#8217;s life: the fact that he never left France during the World War II. As an international figure, he was offered haven from the horrors that were sure to follow by numerous governments and agencies, yet Picasso chose to stay. In this presentation we will explore his reasons for staying in France. Was it an act of patriotism? Was it indifference? Through his works during this time period we will try to uncover his reasons. Does his art speak of the occupation in a positive or negative way? These are only a few of the questions we will explore during the afternoon class on Picasso. N 3/15/2011 10:00 AM 3/15/2011 07:00 PM Series 1085 18TH STREET Boulder CO Highlights of the Collection: Charles Partridge Adams Paintings The CU Art Museum presents two paintings by the noted Colorado landscape painter Charles Partridge Adams, including a never-before-shown, large-scale painting of Rocky Mountain scenery near Estes Park, titled Sunrise on the Mountains, circa 1920, recently conserved by the CU Art Museum, and gifted to the museum&#8217;s permanent collection by the artist&#8217;s sons. The exhibition will also feature the more intimate Untitled (Mountain Landscape), circa 1920, which likely depicts Moraine Park.&#160;&#160; Born in Massachusetts, Charles Partridge Adams moved to Denver at the age of 18 and eventually became perhaps the most prolific and well known of the turn-of-the-century Colorado painters. Receiving artistic encouragement from Helen Henderson Chain, herself a pupil of George Inness, Adams shied away from the grandiose style employed by his contemporaries, preferring to accentuate the emotive in his landscapes and ushering in a long tradition of modernist landscape painting in the Rocky Mountain region. Adams Jr., sons of the late Charles Partridge Adams, CU Art Museum, University of Colorado at Boulder, 86.1825 Photo: J Wells © Regents of the University of Colorado / CU Art Museum N 3/15/2011 10:00 AM 3/15/2011 07:00 PM Series 1085 18TH STREET Boulder CO Highlights of the Collection: Selections from the Andy Warhol Photographic Legacy Program Gift <div>In 2008, the CU Art Museum received 156 photographs by Andy Warhol as a gift of the Andy Warhol Foundation for the Visual Arts as part of the Andy Warhol Photographic Legacy Program. The CU Art Museum will premier 112 of the gifted photographs which include Polaroids and gelatin silver prints featuring celebrities such as Martha Graham, Pel&#233;, and John Denver, as well as portraits of patrons, friends, and anonymous models. Included among the gifted gelatin silver prints are also landscapes and interior settings, both rural and urban, which reveal an aesthetic of the banal as well as the transcendental. The photographs provide valuable insight into the artist&#8217;s blurring of the distinction between &#8220;life&#8221; and &#8220;art&#8221; and his construct of &#8220;the celebrity.&#8221;&#160; The exhibition includes 80 Polaroids and 32 gelatin silver prints taken by the Pop-Art master. </div> <div>&#160;</div> <div> <u>Concurrent Exhibition:</u>&#160;&#160; <em>Warhol In Colorado</em>, an exhibition featuring screen prints, photographs, record album covers and other works by Andy Warhol, will be on view at The University of Denver&#8217;s Victoria H. Myhren Gallery from January 20 to March 13, 2011. The photographs provide valuable insight into the artist&#8217;s blurring of the distinction between &#8220;life&#8221; and &#8220;art&#8221; and his construct of &#8220;the celebrity.&#8221;&#160; The exhibition includes 80 Polaroids and 32 gelatin silver prints taken by the Pop-Art master. </div> <div>&#160;</div> <div> <u>Concurrent Exhibition:</u>&#160;&#160; <em>Warhol In Colorado</em>, an exhibition featuring screen prints, photographs, record album covers and other works by Andy Warhol, will be on view at The University of Denver&#8217;s Victoria H. On most Fridays, we use the traditional South American beverage mat&#233; to create a simple social ritual and develop dynamic community and conversation. N 3/19/2011 12:00 PM 3/19/2011 04:00 PM Series 1085 18TH STREET Boulder CO Highlights of the Collection: Charles Partridge Adams Paintings The CU Art Museum presents two paintings by the noted Colorado landscape painter Charles Partridge Adams, including a never-before-shown, large-scale painting of Rocky Mountain scenery near Estes Park, titled Sunrise on the Mountains, circa 1920, recently conserved by the CU Art Museum, and gifted to the museum&#8217;s permanent collection by the artist&#8217;s sons. The exhibition will also feature the more intimate Untitled (Mountain Landscape), circa 1920, which likely depicts Moraine Park.&#160;&#160; Born in Massachusetts, Charles Partridge Adams moved to Denver at the age of 18 and eventually became perhaps the most prolific and well known of the turn-of-the-century Colorado painters. Receiving artistic encouragement from Helen Henderson Chain, herself a pupil of George Inness, Adams shied away from the grandiose style employed by his contemporaries, preferring to accentuate the emotive in his landscapes and ushering in a long tradition of modernist landscape painting in the Rocky Mountain region. The CU Art Museum will premier 112 of the gifted photographs which include Polaroids and gelatin silver prints featuring celebrities such as Martha Graham, Pel&#233;, and John Denver, as well as portraits of patrons, friends, and anonymous models. Included among the gifted gelatin silver prints are also landscapes and interior settings, both rural and urban, which reveal an aesthetic of the banal as well as the transcendental. The photographs provide valuable insight into the artist&#8217;s blurring of the distinction between &#8220;life&#8221; and &#8220;art&#8221; and his construct of &#8220;the celebrity.&#8221;&#160; The exhibition includes 80 Polaroids and 32 gelatin silver prints taken by the Pop-Art master. </div> <div>&#160;</div> <div> <u>Concurrent Exhibition:</u>&#160;&#160; <em>Warhol In Colorado</em>, an exhibition featuring screen prints, photographs, record album covers and other works by Andy Warhol, will be on view at The University of Denver&#8217;s Victoria H. The photographs provide valuable insight into the artist&#8217;s blurring of the distinction between &#8220;life&#8221; and &#8220;art&#8221; and his construct of &#8220;the celebrity.&#8221;&#160; The exhibition includes 80 Polaroids and 32 gelatin silver prints taken by the Pop-Art master. </div> <div>&#160;</div> <div> <u>Concurrent Exhibition:</u>&#160;&#160; <em>Warhol In Colorado</em>, an exhibition featuring screen prints, photographs, record album covers and other works by Andy Warhol, will be on view at The University of Denver&#8217;s Victoria H. Myhren Gallery from January 20 to March 13, 2011. N 3/24/2011 10:00 AM 3/24/2011 05:00 PM Series 1085 18TH STREET Boulder CO Highlights of the Collection: Charles Partridge Adams Paintings The CU Art Museum presents two paintings by the noted Colorado landscape painter Charles Partridge Adams, including a never-before-shown, large-scale painting of Rocky Mountain scenery near Estes Park, titled Sunrise on the Mountains, circa 1920, recently conserved by the CU Art Museum, and gifted to the museum&#8217;s permanent collection by the artist&#8217;s sons. The exhibition will also feature the more intimate Untitled (Mountain Landscape), circa 1920, which likely depicts Moraine Park.&#160;&#160; Born in Massachusetts, Charles Partridge Adams moved to Denver at the age of 18 and eventually became perhaps the most prolific and well known of the turn-of-the-century Colorado painters. Receiving artistic encouragement from Helen Henderson Chain, herself a pupil of George Inness, Adams shied away from the grandiose style employed by his contemporaries, preferring to accentuate the emotive in his landscapes and ushering in a long tradition of modernist landscape painting in the Rocky Mountain region. N 3/28/2011 07:30 PM 3/28/2011 09:30 PM One Time 1020 18th Street Boulder CO http://www.colorado.edu/campusmap/map.html?bldg=MUS Guest Recital: Nadia Shpachenko, piano Pianist Nadia Shpachenko has performed extensively in solo and chamber music recitals and with orchestras in North America and Europe in venues such as Carnegie Hall in New York, Concertgebouw in Amsterdam, and the Los Angeles County Museum of Art. Described by critics as a "truly inspiring and brilliant pianist...spellbinding in sensitivity and mastery of technique," she most recently toured Mexico with Orquesta de Baja California, performed with the Kharkov Philharmonic, the Ukrainian National Symphony and the Ukrainian National Radio Symphony Orchestras in Ukraine and the San Bernardino Symphony Orchestra in California.<br />&#160;<br />In addition to bringing out new facets of the traditional repertoire, Dr. Shpachenko enjoys applying her deep interpretation to new repertoire by performing and premiering music by contemporary composers. Her recent notable premieres include the World premiere of Ukrainian composer Yury Ishchenko's Piano Concerto No. 2 at the 17th International Contemporary Music Festival "Kiev Music Fest 2006" and the West Coast premiere of Elliott Carter&#8217;s Dialogues for Piano and Chamber Orchestra with the Nimbus Ensemble in Los Angeles. Dr. Shpachenko is also touring a series of lecture-recitals exploring the relations between modern art and modern music, including one on Unorthodox Use of Piano by 20th Century American Composers and one commissioned by the Phillips Collection in Washington, DC to accompany its Modigliani exhibit.<br />&#160;<br />Born in Ukraine, Dr. Shpachenko completed her DMA and MM degrees at the University of Southern California, where she was awarded the title of Outstanding Graduate. Her principal teachers have included such distinguished musicians as John Perry, Victor Rosenbaum, and Victor Derevianko. Winner of numerous international piano competitions, she performed at the International Holland Music Sessions, Aspen, Cliburn, Manchester, Orford, Sarasota, Music Academy of the West, Tel-Hai, and Saluzzo International Music Festivals.<br />&#160;<br />Dr. Shpachenko is currently Assistant Professor of Music at the California State Polytechnic University, Pomona. In addition, she has recently served as visiting faculty at Pomona College, guest lecturer at the California Institute of the Arts, and Artist in Residence at the University of Nevada, Las Vegas. In June 2007 Dr. Shpachenko joined the Associate Piano Faculty of the Sarasota International Music Festival. N 3/29/2011 10:00 AM 3/29/2011 05:00 PM Series 1085 18TH STREET Boulder CO Highlights of the Collection: Charles Partridge Adams Paintings The CU Art Museum presents two paintings by the noted Colorado landscape painter Charles Partridge Adams, including a never-before-shown, large-scale painting of Rocky Mountain scenery near Estes Park, titled Sunrise on the Mountains, circa 1920, recently conserved by the CU Art Museum, and gifted to the museum&#8217;s permanent collection by the artist&#8217;s sons. The exhibition will also feature the more intimate Untitled (Mountain Landscape), circa 1920, which likely depicts Moraine Park.&#160;&#160; Born in Massachusetts, Charles Partridge Adams moved to Denver at the age of 18 and eventually became perhaps the most prolific and well known of the turn-of-the-century Colorado painters. Receiving artistic encouragement from Helen Henderson Chain, herself a pupil of George Inness, Adams shied away from the grandiose style employed by his contemporaries, preferring to accentuate the emotive in his landscapes and ushering in a long tradition of modernist landscape painting in the Rocky Mountain region. Adams Jr., sons of the late Charles Partridge Adams, CU Art Museum, University of Colorado at Boulder, 86.1825 Photo: J Wells © Regents of the University of Colorado / CU Art Museum N 3/29/2011 10:00 AM 3/29/2011 07:00 PM Series 1085 18TH STREET Boulder CO Highlights of the Collection: Selections from the Andy Warhol Photographic Legacy Program Gift <div>In 2008, the CU Art Museum received 156 photographs by Andy Warhol as a gift of the Andy Warhol Foundation for the Visual Arts as part of the Andy Warhol Photographic Legacy Program. The CU Art Museum will premier 112 of the gifted photographs which include Polaroids and gelatin silver prints featuring celebrities such as Martha Graham, Pel&#233;, and John Denver, as well as portraits of patrons, friends, and anonymous models. Included among the gifted gelatin silver prints are also landscapes and interior settings, both rural and urban, which reveal an aesthetic of the banal as well as the transcendental. The photographs provide valuable insight into the artist&#8217;s blurring of the distinction between &#8220;life&#8221; and &#8220;art&#8221; and his construct of &#8220;the celebrity.&#8221;&#160; The exhibition includes 80 Polaroids and 32 gelatin silver prints taken by the Pop-Art master. </div> <div>&#160;</div> <div> <u>Concurrent Exhibition:</u>&#160;&#160; <em>Warhol In Colorado</em>, an exhibition featuring screen prints, photographs, record album covers and other works by Andy Warhol, will be on view at The University of Denver&#8217;s Victoria H. N 3/29/2011 10:00 AM 3/29/2011 05:00 PM Series 1600 PLEASANT ST Boulder CO http://www.colorado.edu/campusmap/map.html?bldg=MAIN Visiting Artist Lecture Series: Shana Moulton <div>Shana Moulton creates evocatively oblique narratives in her video and performance work. Combining an unsettling, wry humor with a low-tech, Pop sensibility, Moulton plays a character whose interaction with the everyday world are both mundane and surreal, in a domestic sphere just slightly askew. Her adventures mirror the insecurities of whole generations while also exploiting stylistic forms and tropes excavated from the recent history of mass-mediated history.</div> <div>&#160;</div> <div>The Visiting Artist Program has been a vital component of the Department of Art &amp; Art History since 1972. N 4/01/2011 10:00 AM 4/01/2011 05:00 PM Series 1085 18TH STREET Boulder CO Highlights of the Collection: Charles Partridge Adams Paintings The CU Art Museum presents two paintings by the noted Colorado landscape painter Charles Partridge Adams, including a never-before-shown, large-scale painting of Rocky Mountain scenery near Estes Park, titled Sunrise on the Mountains, circa 1920, recently conserved by the CU Art Museum, and gifted to the museum&#8217;s permanent collection by the artist&#8217;s sons. The exhibition will also feature the more intimate Untitled (Mountain Landscape), circa 1920, which likely depicts Moraine Park.&#160;&#160; Born in Massachusetts, Charles Partridge Adams moved to Denver at the age of 18 and eventually became perhaps the most prolific and well known of the turn-of-the-century Colorado painters. Receiving artistic encouragement from Helen Henderson Chain, herself a pupil of George Inness, Adams shied away from the grandiose style employed by his contemporaries, preferring to accentuate the emotive in his landscapes and ushering in a long tradition of modernist landscape painting in the Rocky Mountain region. Adams Jr., sons of the late Charles Partridge Adams, CU Art Museum, University of Colorado at Boulder, 86.1825 Photo: J Wells © Regents of the University of Colorado / CU Art Museum N 4/01/2011 10:00 AM 4/01/2011 05:00 PM Series 1085 18TH STREET Boulder CO Highlights of the Collection: Selections from the Andy Warhol Photographic Legacy Program Gift <div>In 2008, the CU Art Museum received 156 photographs by Andy Warhol as a gift of the Andy Warhol Foundation for the Visual Arts as part of the Andy Warhol Photographic Legacy Program. The CU Art Museum will premier 112 of the gifted photographs which include Polaroids and gelatin silver prints featuring celebrities such as Martha Graham, Pel&#233;, and John Denver, as well as portraits of patrons, friends, and anonymous models. Included among the gifted gelatin silver prints are also landscapes and interior settings, both rural and urban, which reveal an aesthetic of the banal as well as the transcendental. The photographs provide valuable insight into the artist&#8217;s blurring of the distinction between &#8220;life&#8221; and &#8220;art&#8221; and his construct of &#8220;the celebrity.&#8221;&#160; The exhibition includes 80 Polaroids and 32 gelatin silver prints taken by the Pop-Art master. </div> <div>&#160;</div> <div> <u>Concurrent Exhibition:</u>&#160;&#160; <em>Warhol In Colorado</em>, an exhibition featuring screen prints, photographs, record album covers and other works by Andy Warhol, will be on view at The University of Denver&#8217;s Victoria H. N 4/03/2011 07:30 PM 4/03/2011 09:30 PM One Time 1020 18th Street Boulder CO http://www.colorado.edu/campusmap/map.html?bldg=MUS 63rd Annual Conference on World Affairs The Conference on World Affairs was founded in 1948 as a forum on international affairs, and expanded rapidly in its early years to encompass the arts, media, science, diplomacy, technology, environment, spirituality, politics, business, medicine, human rights, and so on. Roger Ebert, who has participated in the CWA for thirty-eight consecutive years, refers to the CWA as &#8220;the Conference on Everything Conceivable.&#8221;<br /><br /> Each April 110 participants representing a wide range of backgrounds gather in Boulder for what The New York Times calls &#8220;a week-long extravaganza of discussion and debate&#8221; on over 200 panels, plenaries and performances.<br /><br /> All events are free and open to the public.<br /><br /> Learn more about the Conference on World Affairs and their signature events at their <a target="_blank" href="http://www.colorado.edu/cwa">website</a>. N 4/04/2011 07:30 PM 4/04/2011 09:30 PM One Time Cancelled 1020 18th Street Boulder CO http://www.colorado.edu/campusmap/map.html?bldg=MUS 63rd Annual Conference on World Affairs The Conference on World Affairs was founded in 1948 as a forum on international affairs, and expanded rapidly in its early years to encompass the arts, media, science, diplomacy, technology, environment, spirituality, politics, business, medicine, human rights, and so on. Roger Ebert, who has participated in the CWA for thirty-eight consecutive years, refers to the CWA as &#8220;the Conference on Everything Conceivable.&#8221;<br /><br /> Each April 110 participants representing a wide range of backgrounds gather in Boulder for what The New York Times calls &#8220;a week-long extravaganza of discussion and debate&#8221; on over 200 panels, plenaries and performances.<br /><br /> All events are free and open to the public.<br /><br /> Learn more about the Conference on World Affairs and their signature events at their <a target="_blank" href="http://www.colorado.edu/cwa">website</a>. N 4/05/2011 10:00 AM 4/05/2011 07:00 PM Series 1085 18TH STREET Boulder CO Highlights of the Collection: Charles Partridge Adams Paintings The CU Art Museum presents two paintings by the noted Colorado landscape painter Charles Partridge Adams, including a never-before-shown, large-scale painting of Rocky Mountain scenery near Estes Park, titled Sunrise on the Mountains, circa 1920, recently conserved by the CU Art Museum, and gifted to the museum&#8217;s permanent collection by the artist&#8217;s sons. The exhibition will also feature the more intimate Untitled (Mountain Landscape), circa 1920, which likely depicts Moraine Park.&#160;&#160; Born in Massachusetts, Charles Partridge Adams moved to Denver at the age of 18 and eventually became perhaps the most prolific and well known of the turn-of-the-century Colorado painters. Receiving artistic encouragement from Helen Henderson Chain, herself a pupil of George Inness, Adams shied away from the grandiose style employed by his contemporaries, preferring to accentuate the emotive in his landscapes and ushering in a long tradition of modernist landscape painting in the Rocky Mountain region. Adams Jr., sons of the late Charles Partridge Adams, CU Art Museum, University of Colorado at Boulder, 86.1825 Photo: J Wells © Regents of the University of Colorado / CU Art Museum N 4/05/2011 10:00 AM 4/05/2011 07:00 PM Series 1085 18TH STREET Boulder CO Highlights of the Collection: Selections from the Andy Warhol Photographic Legacy Program Gift <div>In 2008, the CU Art Museum received 156 photographs by Andy Warhol as a gift of the Andy Warhol Foundation for the Visual Arts as part of the Andy Warhol Photographic Legacy Program. The CU Art Museum will premier 112 of the gifted photographs which include Polaroids and gelatin silver prints featuring celebrities such as Martha Graham, Pel&#233;, and John Denver, as well as portraits of patrons, friends, and anonymous models. Included among the gifted gelatin silver prints are also landscapes and interior settings, both rural and urban, which reveal an aesthetic of the banal as well as the transcendental. The photographs provide valuable insight into the artist&#8217;s blurring of the distinction between &#8220;life&#8221; and &#8220;art&#8221; and his construct of &#8220;the celebrity.&#8221;&#160; The exhibition includes 80 Polaroids and 32 gelatin silver prints taken by the Pop-Art master. </div> <div>&#160;</div> <div> <u>Concurrent Exhibition:</u>&#160;&#160; <em>Warhol In Colorado</em>, an exhibition featuring screen prints, photographs, record album covers and other works by Andy Warhol, will be on view at The University of Denver&#8217;s Victoria H. Myhren Gallery from January 20 to March 13, 2011. Also included are 55 Polaroids and silver prints gifted to the university by the Andy Warhol Photographic Legacy Program in 2008.&#160; Details at <a href="http://myhrengallery.wordpress.com/our-namesake/">www.du.edu/art/myhrengallery </a><br /></div> <div> <br /> </div> <div>&#160;</div> <div>&#160;</div> Jennifer Conrad jennifer.conrad@colorado.edu Arts & Culture-Visual Arts,Arts and Sciences,CU Art Museum,Exhibits & Gallery Shows-Temporary / Visiting Exhibits Main Campus Visual Arts Complex CU Art Museum <li>Everyone</li> Free and open to the public Image credit: Andy Warhol, American (1928-1987) 'Pele,' 1977 Polacolor Type 108 4 ¼ x 3 3/8 inches Gift of The Andy Warhol Foundation for the Visual Arts, Inc., The Andy Warhol Photographic Legacy Program, CU Art Museum, University of Colorado at Boulder, 2008.2.39 © The Andy Warhol Foundation for the Visual Arts N 4/05/2011 10:00 AM 4/05/2011 07:00 PM Series 1085 18TH STREET Boulder CO Stages: 50 Years of Theatre at CU Celebrating the golden anniversary of the theater department through colorful photographs, costumes and props. N 4/07/2011 09:00 PM 4/07/2011 11:30 PM Series 1669 EUCLID AV Boulder CO http://www.colorado.edu/campusmap/map.html?bldg=UMC Doctoral defense/final exam deadline <div>Doctoral students must pass their <em>PhD dissertation defense or doctoral final examination</em> by this date in order to graduate in May.&#160; The Graduate School must have written notification of final examination and thesis committee <u>two weeks prior</u> to exam.&#160; This information should be provided on the Doctoral Examination Report and the Leaflet.</div> Graduate Student Services 303-492-8220 gradinfo@colorado.edu Academic Calendar,Graduate School,Graduate School-Academic Deadlines <li>Students</li><li>Faculty</li><li>Staff</li> Y 4/08/2011 4/08/2011 One Time 63rd Annual Conference on World Affairs The Conference on World Affairs was founded in 1948 as a forum on international affairs, and expanded rapidly in its early years to encompass the arts, media, science, diplomacy, technology, environment, spirituality, politics, business, medicine, human rights, and so on. Roger Ebert, who has participated in the CWA for thirty-eight consecutive years, refers to the CWA as &#8220;the Conference on Everything Conceivable.&#8221;<br /><br /> Each April 110 participants representing a wide range of backgrounds gather in Boulder for what The New York Times calls &#8220;a week-long extravaganza of discussion and debate&#8221; on over 200 panels, plenaries and performances.<br /><br /> All events are free and open to the public.<br /><br /> Learn more about the Conference on World Affairs and their signature events at their <a target="_blank" href="http://www.colorado.edu/cwa">website</a>. N 4/08/2011 10:00 AM 4/08/2011 05:00 PM Series 1085 18TH STREET Boulder CO Highlights of the Collection: Charles Partridge Adams Paintings The CU Art Museum presents two paintings by the noted Colorado landscape painter Charles Partridge Adams, including a never-before-shown, large-scale painting of Rocky Mountain scenery near Estes Park, titled Sunrise on the Mountains, circa 1920, recently conserved by the CU Art Museum, and gifted to the museum&#8217;s permanent collection by the artist&#8217;s sons. The exhibition will also feature the more intimate Untitled (Mountain Landscape), circa 1920, which likely depicts Moraine Park.&#160;&#160; Born in Massachusetts, Charles Partridge Adams moved to Denver at the age of 18 and eventually became perhaps the most prolific and well known of the turn-of-the-century Colorado painters. Receiving artistic encouragement from Helen Henderson Chain, herself a pupil of George Inness, Adams shied away from the grandiose style employed by his contemporaries, preferring to accentuate the emotive in his landscapes and ushering in a long tradition of modernist landscape painting in the Rocky Mountain region. Adams Jr., sons of the late Charles Partridge Adams, CU Art Museum, University of Colorado at Boulder, 86.1825 Photo: J Wells © Regents of the University of Colorado / CU Art Museum N 4/08/2011 10:00 AM 4/08/2011 05:00 PM Series 1085 18TH STREET Boulder CO Highlights of the Collection: Selections from the Andy Warhol Photographic Legacy Program Gift <div>In 2008, the CU Art Museum received 156 photographs by Andy Warhol as a gift of the Andy Warhol Foundation for the Visual Arts as part of the Andy Warhol Photographic Legacy Program. The CU Art Museum will premier 112 of the gifted photographs which include Polaroids and gelatin silver prints featuring celebrities such as Martha Graham, Pel&#233;, and John Denver, as well as portraits of patrons, friends, and anonymous models. Included among the gifted gelatin silver prints are also landscapes and interior settings, both rural and urban, which reveal an aesthetic of the banal as well as the transcendental. The photographs provide valuable insight into the artist&#8217;s blurring of the distinction between &#8220;life&#8221; and &#8220;art&#8221; and his construct of &#8220;the celebrity.&#8221;&#160; The exhibition includes 80 Polaroids and 32 gelatin silver prints taken by the Pop-Art master. </div> <div>&#160;</div> <div> <u>Concurrent Exhibition:</u>&#160;&#160; <em>Warhol In Colorado</em>, an exhibition featuring screen prints, photographs, record album covers and other works by Andy Warhol, will be on view at The University of Denver&#8217;s Victoria H. Myhren Gallery from January 20 to March 13, 2011. N 4/08/2011 07:30 PM 4/08/2011 09:30 PM One Time 1020 18th Street Boulder CO http://www.colorado.edu/campusmap/map.html?bldg=MUS CU on the Weekend - Baseball and the American Dream in History What do Jackie Robinson and Jackie Mitchell, A-Rod and Albert Spalding, Marvin Mitchell and Mannie Ramirez, O&#8217;Malley and O&#8217;Doul have in common? A shared history of baseball and a belief in the American dream. This class will link baseball to topics foundational to the American dream: Equality (race), Liberty (women), Prosperity (business and work), Mobility (expansion), and Opportunity (globalization). Professor Tom Zeiler&#8217;s class is for novices and experts alike who wish to study historical trends. This class is not about statistics, games, or the field of dreams but all of these will play a part in our attempt to see what became of the American dream. The international pastime shows us how to learn about ourselves as well, for as historian Jacques Barzun wrote, &#8220;whoever wants to know the heart and mind of America better learn baseball.&#8221; CU on the Weekend 303-492-9881 weekend@colorado.edu Continuing Education,Lectures & Seminars,Lectures & Seminars-Lectures Main Campus Eaton Humanities 250 <li>Everyone</li> Tuition: $25. N 4/12/2011 10:00 AM 4/12/2011 07:00 PM Series 1085 18TH STREET Boulder CO Highlights of the Collection: Charles Partridge Adams Paintings The CU Art Museum presents two paintings by the noted Colorado landscape painter Charles Partridge Adams, including a never-before-shown, large-scale painting of Rocky Mountain scenery near Estes Park, titled Sunrise on the Mountains, circa 1920, recently conserved by the CU Art Museum, and gifted to the museum&#8217;s permanent collection by the artist&#8217;s sons. The exhibition will also feature the more intimate Untitled (Mountain Landscape), circa 1920, which likely depicts Moraine Park.&#160;&#160; Born in Massachusetts, Charles Partridge Adams moved to Denver at the age of 18 and eventually became perhaps the most prolific and well known of the turn-of-the-century Colorado painters. Receiving artistic encouragement from Helen Henderson Chain, herself a pupil of George Inness, Adams shied away from the grandiose style employed by his contemporaries, preferring to accentuate the emotive in his landscapes and ushering in a long tradition of modernist landscape painting in the Rocky Mountain region. Jennifer Conrad jennifer.conrad@colorado.edu Arts & Culture-Visual Arts,Arts and Sciences,CU Art Museum,Exhibits & Gallery Shows-Temporary / Visiting Exhibits Main Campus Visual Arts Complex CU Art Museum <li>Everyone</li> Free and open to the public Image credit: Charles Partridge Adams, American (1858-1942) 'Sunrise on the Mountains at the Head of Moraine Park, Near Estes Park, Colorado,' c. 1920s oil on canvas 40 x 60 inches Gift of Philip, Albert and Charles P. Adams Jr., sons of the late Charles Partridge Adams, CU Art Museum, University of Colorado at Boulder, 86.1825 Photo: J Wells © Regents of the University of Colorado / CU Art Museum N 4/12/2011 10:00 AM 4/12/2011 07:00 PM Series 1085 18TH STREET Boulder CO Highlights of the Collection: Selections from the Andy Warhol Photographic Legacy Program Gift <div>In 2008, the CU Art Museum received 156 photographs by Andy Warhol as a gift of the Andy Warhol Foundation for the Visual Arts as part of the Andy Warhol Photographic Legacy Program. The CU Art Museum will premier 112 of the gifted photographs which include Polaroids and gelatin silver prints featuring celebrities such as Martha Graham, Pel&#233;, and John Denver, as well as portraits of patrons, friends, and anonymous models. Included among the gifted gelatin silver prints are also landscapes and interior settings, both rural and urban, which reveal an aesthetic of the banal as well as the transcendental. The photographs provide valuable insight into the artist&#8217;s blurring of the distinction between &#8220;life&#8221; and &#8220;art&#8221; and his construct of &#8220;the celebrity.&#8221;&#160; The exhibition includes 80 Polaroids and 32 gelatin silver prints taken by the Pop-Art master. </div> <div>&#160;</div> <div> <u>Concurrent Exhibition:</u>&#160;&#160; <em>Warhol In Colorado</em>, an exhibition featuring screen prints, photographs, record album covers and other works by Andy Warhol, will be on view at The University of Denver&#8217;s Victoria H. Myhren Gallery from January 20 to March 13, 2011. Also included are 55 Polaroids and silver prints gifted to the university by the Andy Warhol Photographic Legacy Program in 2008.&#160; Details at <a href="http://myhrengallery.wordpress.com/our-namesake/">www.du.edu/art/myhrengallery </a><br /></div> <div> <br /> </div> <div>&#160;</div> <div>&#160;</div> Jennifer Conrad jennifer.conrad@colorado.edu Arts & Culture-Visual Arts,Arts and Sciences,CU Art Museum,Exhibits & Gallery Shows-Temporary / Visiting Exhibits Main Campus Visual Arts Complex CU Art Museum <li>Everyone</li> Free and open to the public Image credit: Andy Warhol, American (1928-1987) 'Pele,' 1977 Polacolor Type 108 4 ¼ x 3 3/8 inches Gift of The Andy Warhol Foundation for the Visual Arts, Inc., The Andy Warhol Photographic Legacy Program, CU Art Museum, University of Colorado at Boulder, 2008.2.39 © The Andy Warhol Foundation for the Visual Arts N 4/12/2011 10:00 AM 4/12/2011 07:00 PM Series 1085 18TH STREET Boulder CO Stages: 50 Years of Theatre at CU Celebrating the golden anniversary of the theater department through colorful photographs, costumes and props. N 4/12/2011 10:00 AM 4/12/2011 05:00 PM Series 1600 PLEASANT ST Boulder CO http://www.colorado.edu/campusmap/map.html?bldg=MAIN Visiting Artist Lecture Series: William Basinski <div>William Basinski is a classically trained musician and composer who has been working in experimental media for over 25 years. Inspired by minimalists such as Steve Reich and Brian Eno, he has developed his own vocabulary using tape loops and old reel-to-reel tape decks.</div> <div>&#160;</div> <div>This lecture is made possible by a grant from the James and Rebecca Roser visiting artist grant, and collaborations with the school of Music and Communikey Electronic Art.</div> <div>&#160;</div> <div>The Visiting Artist Program has been a vital component of the Department of Art &amp; Art History since 1972. N 4/15/2011 10:00 AM 4/15/2011 05:00 PM Series 1085 18TH STREET Boulder CO Highlights of the Collection: Charles Partridge Adams Paintings The CU Art Museum presents two paintings by the noted Colorado landscape painter Charles Partridge Adams, including a never-before-shown, large-scale painting of Rocky Mountain scenery near Estes Park, titled Sunrise on the Mountains, circa 1920, recently conserved by the CU Art Museum, and gifted to the museum&#8217;s permanent collection by the artist&#8217;s sons. The exhibition will also feature the more intimate Untitled (Mountain Landscape), circa 1920, which likely depicts Moraine Park.&#160;&#160; Born in Massachusetts, Charles Partridge Adams moved to Denver at the age of 18 and eventually became perhaps the most prolific and well known of the turn-of-the-century Colorado painters. Receiving artistic encouragement from Helen Henderson Chain, herself a pupil of George Inness, Adams shied away from the grandiose style employed by his contemporaries, preferring to accentuate the emotive in his landscapes and ushering in a long tradition of modernist landscape painting in the Rocky Mountain region. The CU Art Museum will premier 112 of the gifted photographs which include Polaroids and gelatin silver prints featuring celebrities such as Martha Graham, Pel&#233;, and John Denver, as well as portraits of patrons, friends, and anonymous models. Included among the gifted gelatin silver prints are also landscapes and interior settings, both rural and urban, which reveal an aesthetic of the banal as well as the transcendental. The photographs provide valuable insight into the artist&#8217;s blurring of the distinction between &#8220;life&#8221; and &#8220;art&#8221; and his construct of &#8220;the celebrity.&#8221;&#160; The exhibition includes 80 Polaroids and 32 gelatin silver prints taken by the Pop-Art master. </div> <div>&#160;</div> <div> <u>Concurrent Exhibition:</u>&#160;&#160; <em>Warhol In Colorado</em>, an exhibition featuring screen prints, photographs, record album covers and other works by Andy Warhol, will be on view at The University of Denver&#8217;s Victoria H. By the mid-90s, she was being hailed as a &#8220;savior of the written word.&#8221; Over the last decade, Winfrey has been deemed an &#8220;inspirational phenomenon,&#8221; &#8220;the world&#8217;s most powerful woman,&#8221; and a political &#8220;kingmaker,&#8221; thanks to her endorsement of Barack Obama. Through her talk show, magazine, website, seminars, charity work, and public appearances, Winfrey&#8217;s influence has been enormous. Associate Professor Janice Peck&#8217;s class will examine that influence. Among the developments that will be covered are the eclipse of the second wave women&#8217;s movement by post-feminism, the emergence of the &#8220;recovery movement,&#8221; the revival of personal growth forms of spirituality, and the rise of the neoliberal political-economic agenda that has dominated the political landscape of the U.S. since the 1980s. N 4/18/2011 10:00 AM 4/18/2011 05:00 PM Series 1085 18TH STREET Boulder CO Highlights of the Collection: Charles Partridge Adams Paintings The CU Art Museum presents two paintings by the noted Colorado landscape painter Charles Partridge Adams, including a never-before-shown, large-scale painting of Rocky Mountain scenery near Estes Park, titled Sunrise on the Mountains, circa 1920, recently conserved by the CU Art Museum, and gifted to the museum&#8217;s permanent collection by the artist&#8217;s sons. The exhibition will also feature the more intimate Untitled (Mountain Landscape), circa 1920, which likely depicts Moraine Park.&#160;&#160; Born in Massachusetts, Charles Partridge Adams moved to Denver at the age of 18 and eventually became perhaps the most prolific and well known of the turn-of-the-century Colorado painters. Receiving artistic encouragement from Helen Henderson Chain, herself a pupil of George Inness, Adams shied away from the grandiose style employed by his contemporaries, preferring to accentuate the emotive in his landscapes and ushering in a long tradition of modernist landscape painting in the Rocky Mountain region. Jennifer Conrad jennifer.conrad@colorado.edu Arts & Culture-Visual Arts,Arts and Sciences,CU Art Museum,Exhibits & Gallery Shows-Temporary / Visiting Exhibits Main Campus Visual Arts Complex CU Art Museum <li>Everyone</li> Free and open to the public Image credit: Charles Partridge Adams, American (1858-1942) 'Sunrise on the Mountains at the Head of Moraine Park, Near Estes Park, Colorado,' c. 1920s oil on canvas 40 x 60 inches Gift of Philip, Albert and Charles P. Adams Jr., sons of the late Charles Partridge Adams, CU Art Museum, University of Colorado at Boulder, 86.1825 Photo: J Wells © Regents of the University of Colorado / CU Art Museum N 4/18/2011 10:00 AM 4/18/2011 05:00 PM Series 1085 18TH STREET Boulder CO Highlights of the Collection: Selections from the Andy Warhol Photographic Legacy Program Gift <div>In 2008, the CU Art Museum received 156 photographs by Andy Warhol as a gift of the Andy Warhol Foundation for the Visual Arts as part of the Andy Warhol Photographic Legacy Program. The CU Art Museum will premier 112 of the gifted photographs which include Polaroids and gelatin silver prints featuring celebrities such as Martha Graham, Pel&#233;, and John Denver, as well as portraits of patrons, friends, and anonymous models. Included among the gifted gelatin silver prints are also landscapes and interior settings, both rural and urban, which reveal an aesthetic of the banal as well as the transcendental. The photographs provide valuable insight into the artist&#8217;s blurring of the distinction between &#8220;life&#8221; and &#8220;art&#8221; and his construct of &#8220;the celebrity.&#8221;&#160; The exhibition includes 80 Polaroids and 32 gelatin silver prints taken by the Pop-Art master. </div> <div>&#160;</div> <div> <u>Concurrent Exhibition:</u>&#160;&#160; <em>Warhol In Colorado</em>, an exhibition featuring screen prints, photographs, record album covers and other works by Andy Warhol, will be on view at The University of Denver&#8217;s Victoria H. Myhren Gallery from January 20 to March 13, 2011. Also included are 55 Polaroids and silver prints gifted to the university by the Andy Warhol Photographic Legacy Program in 2008.&#160; Details at <a href="http://myhrengallery.wordpress.com/our-namesake/">www.du.edu/art/myhrengallery </a><br /></div> <div> <br /> </div> <div>&#160;</div> <div>&#160;</div> Jennifer Conrad jennifer.conrad@colorado.edu Arts & Culture-Visual Arts,Arts and Sciences,CU Art Museum,Exhibits & Gallery Shows-Temporary / Visiting Exhibits Main Campus Visual Arts Complex CU Art Museum <li>Everyone</li> Free and open to the public Image credit: Andy Warhol, American (1928-1987) 'Pele,' 1977 Polacolor Type 108 4 ¼ x 3 3/8 inches Gift of The Andy Warhol Foundation for the Visual Arts, Inc., The Andy Warhol Photographic Legacy Program, CU Art Museum, University of Colorado at Boulder, 2008.2.39 © The Andy Warhol Foundation for the Visual Arts N 4/18/2011 10:00 AM 4/18/2011 05:00 PM Series 1085 18TH STREET Boulder CO Stages: 50 Years of Theatre at CU Celebrating the golden anniversary of the theater department through colorful photographs, costumes and props. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts in Washington, D.C. in 1971. &#160;Leonard Bernstein combined the Latin Tridentine Mass of the Roman Catholic Church with&#160;English-language texts and songs to explore a crisis of faith, blending traditional church music with various popular styles including blues and rock-and-roll. </div> <div>&#160;</div> <div>You are welcome to bring your lunch and water to the Brown Bag Preview, but please avoid bringing coffee, tea, and soda into the Music Theatre. <br /></div> CU Presents Box Office 303-492-8008 musictix@colorado.edu Arts & Culture-Performing Arts,College & School Events,College of Music,College of Music-CU Opera,College of Music-CU Presents,College of Music-Voice Main Campus Imig Music Music Theatre <li>Everyone</li> Free and open to the public. N 4/21/2011 10:00 AM 4/21/2011 05:00 PM Series 1085 18TH STREET Boulder CO Highlights of the Collection: Charles Partridge Adams Paintings The CU Art Museum presents two paintings by the noted Colorado landscape painter Charles Partridge Adams, including a never-before-shown, large-scale painting of Rocky Mountain scenery near Estes Park, titled Sunrise on the Mountains, circa 1920, recently conserved by the CU Art Museum, and gifted to the museum&#8217;s permanent collection by the artist&#8217;s sons. The exhibition will also feature the more intimate Untitled (Mountain Landscape), circa 1920, which likely depicts Moraine Park.&#160;&#160; Born in Massachusetts, Charles Partridge Adams moved to Denver at the age of 18 and eventually became perhaps the most prolific and well known of the turn-of-the-century Colorado painters. Receiving artistic encouragement from Helen Henderson Chain, herself a pupil of George Inness, Adams shied away from the grandiose style employed by his contemporaries, preferring to accentuate the emotive in his landscapes and ushering in a long tradition of modernist landscape painting in the Rocky Mountain region. Adams Jr., sons of the late Charles Partridge Adams, CU Art Museum, University of Colorado at Boulder, 86.1825 Photo: J Wells © Regents of the University of Colorado / CU Art Museum N 4/21/2011 10:00 AM 4/21/2011 05:00 PM Series 1085 18TH STREET Boulder CO Highlights of the Collection: Selections from the Andy Warhol Photographic Legacy Program Gift <div>In 2008, the CU Art Museum received 156 photographs by Andy Warhol as a gift of the Andy Warhol Foundation for the Visual Arts as part of the Andy Warhol Photographic Legacy Program. The CU Art Museum will premier 112 of the gifted photographs which include Polaroids and gelatin silver prints featuring celebrities such as Martha Graham, Pel&#233;, and John Denver, as well as portraits of patrons, friends, and anonymous models. Included among the gifted gelatin silver prints are also landscapes and interior settings, both rural and urban, which reveal an aesthetic of the banal as well as the transcendental. The photographs provide valuable insight into the artist&#8217;s blurring of the distinction between &#8220;life&#8221; and &#8220;art&#8221; and his construct of &#8220;the celebrity.&#8221;&#160; The exhibition includes 80 Polaroids and 32 gelatin silver prints taken by the Pop-Art master. </div> <div>&#160;</div> <div> <u>Concurrent Exhibition:</u>&#160;&#160; <em>Warhol In Colorado</em>, an exhibition featuring screen prints, photographs, record album covers and other works by Andy Warhol, will be on view at The University of Denver&#8217;s Victoria H. Myhren Gallery from January 20 to March 13, 2011. Also included are 55 Polaroids and silver prints gifted to the university by the Andy Warhol Photographic Legacy Program in 2008.&#160; Details at <a href="http://myhrengallery.wordpress.com/our-namesake/">www.du.edu/art/myhrengallery </a><br /></div> <div> <br /> </div> <div>&#160;</div> <div>&#160;</div> Jennifer Conrad jennifer.conrad@colorado.edu Arts & Culture-Visual Arts,Arts and Sciences,CU Art Museum,Exhibits & Gallery Shows-Temporary / Visiting Exhibits Main Campus Visual Arts Complex CU Art Museum <li>Everyone</li> Free and open to the public Image credit: Andy Warhol, American (1928-1987) 'Pele,' 1977 Polacolor Type 108 4 ¼ x 3 3/8 inches Gift of The Andy Warhol Foundation for the Visual Arts, Inc., The Andy Warhol Photographic Legacy Program, CU Art Museum, University of Colorado at Boulder, 2008.2.39 © The Andy Warhol Foundation for the Visual Arts N 4/21/2011 10:00 AM 4/21/2011 05:00 PM Series 1085 18TH STREET Boulder CO Stages: 50 Years of Theatre at CU Celebrating the golden anniversary of the theater department through colorful photographs, costumes and props. On most Fridays, we use the traditional South American beverage mat&#233; to create a simple social ritual and develop dynamic community and conversation. N 4/25/2011 10:00 AM 4/25/2011 05:00 PM Series 1085 18TH STREET Boulder CO Highlights of the Collection: Charles Partridge Adams Paintings The CU Art Museum presents two paintings by the noted Colorado landscape painter Charles Partridge Adams, including a never-before-shown, large-scale painting of Rocky Mountain scenery near Estes Park, titled Sunrise on the Mountains, circa 1920, recently conserved by the CU Art Museum, and gifted to the museum&#8217;s permanent collection by the artist&#8217;s sons. The exhibition will also feature the more intimate Untitled (Mountain Landscape), circa 1920, which likely depicts Moraine Park.&#160;&#160; Born in Massachusetts, Charles Partridge Adams moved to Denver at the age of 18 and eventually became perhaps the most prolific and well known of the turn-of-the-century Colorado painters. Receiving artistic encouragement from Helen Henderson Chain, herself a pupil of George Inness, Adams shied away from the grandiose style employed by his contemporaries, preferring to accentuate the emotive in his landscapes and ushering in a long tradition of modernist landscape painting in the Rocky Mountain region. Adams Jr., sons of the late Charles Partridge Adams, CU Art Museum, University of Colorado at Boulder, 86.1825 Photo: J Wells © Regents of the University of Colorado / CU Art Museum N 4/25/2011 10:00 AM 4/25/2011 05:00 PM Series 1085 18TH STREET Boulder CO Highlights of the Collection: Selections from the Andy Warhol Photographic Legacy Program Gift <div>In 2008, the CU Art Museum received 156 photographs by Andy Warhol as a gift of the Andy Warhol Foundation for the Visual Arts as part of the Andy Warhol Photographic Legacy Program. The CU Art Museum will premier 112 of the gifted photographs which include Polaroids and gelatin silver prints featuring celebrities such as Martha Graham, Pel&#233;, and John Denver, as well as portraits of patrons, friends, and anonymous models. Included among the gifted gelatin silver prints are also landscapes and interior settings, both rural and urban, which reveal an aesthetic of the banal as well as the transcendental. The photographs provide valuable insight into the artist&#8217;s blurring of the distinction between &#8220;life&#8221; and &#8220;art&#8221; and his construct of &#8220;the celebrity.&#8221;&#160; The exhibition includes 80 Polaroids and 32 gelatin silver prints taken by the Pop-Art master. </div> <div>&#160;</div> <div> <u>Concurrent Exhibition:</u>&#160;&#160; <em>Warhol In Colorado</em>, an exhibition featuring screen prints, photographs, record album covers and other works by Andy Warhol, will be on view at The University of Denver&#8217;s Victoria H. Myhren Gallery from January 20 to March 13, 2011. N 4/28/2011 10:00 AM 4/28/2011 05:00 PM Series 1085 18TH STREET Boulder CO Highlights of the Collection: Charles Partridge Adams Paintings The CU Art Museum presents two paintings by the noted Colorado landscape painter Charles Partridge Adams, including a never-before-shown, large-scale painting of Rocky Mountain scenery near Estes Park, titled Sunrise on the Mountains, circa 1920, recently conserved by the CU Art Museum, and gifted to the museum&#8217;s permanent collection by the artist&#8217;s sons. The exhibition will also feature the more intimate Untitled (Mountain Landscape), circa 1920, which likely depicts Moraine Park.&#160;&#160; Born in Massachusetts, Charles Partridge Adams moved to Denver at the age of 18 and eventually became perhaps the most prolific and well known of the turn-of-the-century Colorado painters. Receiving artistic encouragement from Helen Henderson Chain, herself a pupil of George Inness, Adams shied away from the grandiose style employed by his contemporaries, preferring to accentuate the emotive in his landscapes and ushering in a long tradition of modernist landscape painting in the Rocky Mountain region. Adams Jr., sons of the late Charles Partridge Adams, CU Art Museum, University of Colorado at Boulder, 86.1825 Photo: J Wells © Regents of the University of Colorado / CU Art Museum N 4/28/2011 10:00 AM 4/28/2011 05:00 PM Series 1085 18TH STREET Boulder CO Highlights of the Collection: Selections from the Andy Warhol Photographic Legacy Program Gift <div>In 2008, the CU Art Museum received 156 photographs by Andy Warhol as a gift of the Andy Warhol Foundation for the Visual Arts as part of the Andy Warhol Photographic Legacy Program. The CU Art Museum will premier 112 of the gifted photographs which include Polaroids and gelatin silver prints featuring celebrities such as Martha Graham, Pel&#233;, and John Denver, as well as portraits of patrons, friends, and anonymous models. Included among the gifted gelatin silver prints are also landscapes and interior settings, both rural and urban, which reveal an aesthetic of the banal as well as the transcendental. The photographs provide valuable insight into the artist&#8217;s blurring of the distinction between &#8220;life&#8221; and &#8220;art&#8221; and his construct of &#8220;the celebrity.&#8221;&#160; The exhibition includes 80 Polaroids and 32 gelatin silver prints taken by the Pop-Art master. </div> <div>&#160;</div> <div> <u>Concurrent Exhibition:</u>&#160;&#160; <em>Warhol In Colorado</em>, an exhibition featuring screen prints, photographs, record album covers and other works by Andy Warhol, will be on view at The University of Denver&#8217;s Victoria H. Myhren Gallery from January 20 to March 13, 2011. N 4/29/2011 10:00 AM 4/29/2011 05:00 PM Series 1600 PLEASANT ST Boulder CO http://www.colorado.edu/campusmap/map.html?bldg=MAIN Oasis Community Circle <div>Oasis invites you to share mat&#233; and join our community circle. On most Fridays, we use the traditional South American beverage mat&#233; to create a simple social ritual and develop dynamic community and conversation. This ritual is used to cultivate an inclusive community of mutual support, to help us foster rich relationships, and to uplift our spirits. N 5/03/2011 10:00 AM 5/03/2011 07:00 PM Series 1085 18TH STREET Boulder CO Highlights of the Collection: Charles Partridge Adams Paintings The CU Art Museum presents two paintings by the noted Colorado landscape painter Charles Partridge Adams, including a never-before-shown, large-scale painting of Rocky Mountain scenery near Estes Park, titled Sunrise on the Mountains, circa 1920, recently conserved by the CU Art Museum, and gifted to the museum&#8217;s permanent collection by the artist&#8217;s sons. The exhibition will also feature the more intimate Untitled (Mountain Landscape), circa 1920, which likely depicts Moraine Park.&#160;&#160; Born in Massachusetts, Charles Partridge Adams moved to Denver at the age of 18 and eventually became perhaps the most prolific and well known of the turn-of-the-century Colorado painters. Receiving artistic encouragement from Helen Henderson Chain, herself a pupil of George Inness, Adams shied away from the grandiose style employed by his contemporaries, preferring to accentuate the emotive in his landscapes and ushering in a long tradition of modernist landscape painting in the Rocky Mountain region. Jennifer Conrad jennifer.conrad@colorado.edu Arts & Culture-Visual Arts,Arts and Sciences,CU Art Museum,Exhibits & Gallery Shows-Temporary / Visiting Exhibits Main Campus Visual Arts Complex CU Art Museum <li>Everyone</li> Free and open to the public Image credit: Charles Partridge Adams, American (1858-1942) 'Sunrise on the Mountains at the Head of Moraine Park, Near Estes Park, Colorado,' c. 1920s oil on canvas 40 x 60 inches Gift of Philip, Albert and Charles P. Adams Jr., sons of the late Charles Partridge Adams, CU Art Museum, University of Colorado at Boulder, 86.1825 Photo: J Wells © Regents of the University of Colorado / CU Art Museum N 5/03/2011 10:00 AM 5/03/2011 07:00 PM Series 1085 18TH STREET Boulder CO Highlights of the Collection: Selections from the Andy Warhol Photographic Legacy Program Gift <div>In 2008, the CU Art Museum received 156 photographs by Andy Warhol as a gift of the Andy Warhol Foundation for the Visual Arts as part of the Andy Warhol Photographic Legacy Program. The CU Art Museum will premier 112 of the gifted photographs which include Polaroids and gelatin silver prints featuring celebrities such as Martha Graham, Pel&#233;, and John Denver, as well as portraits of patrons, friends, and anonymous models. Included among the gifted gelatin silver prints are also landscapes and interior settings, both rural and urban, which reveal an aesthetic of the banal as well as the transcendental. The photographs provide valuable insight into the artist&#8217;s blurring of the distinction between &#8220;life&#8221; and &#8220;art&#8221; and his construct of &#8220;the celebrity.&#8221;&#160; The exhibition includes 80 Polaroids and 32 gelatin silver prints taken by the Pop-Art master. </div> <div>&#160;</div> <div> <u>Concurrent Exhibition:</u>&#160;&#160; <em>Warhol In Colorado</em>, an exhibition featuring screen prints, photographs, record album covers and other works by Andy Warhol, will be on view at The University of Denver&#8217;s Victoria H. Myhren Gallery from January 20 to March 13, 2011. Also included are 55 Polaroids and silver prints gifted to the university by the Andy Warhol Photographic Legacy Program in 2008.&#160; Details at <a href="http://myhrengallery.wordpress.com/our-namesake/">www.du.edu/art/myhrengallery </a><br /></div> <div> <br /> </div> <div>&#160;</div> <div>&#160;</div> Jennifer Conrad jennifer.conrad@colorado.edu Arts & Culture-Visual Arts,Arts and Sciences,CU Art Museum,Exhibits & Gallery Shows-Temporary / Visiting Exhibits Main Campus Visual Arts Complex CU Art Museum <li>Everyone</li> Free and open to the public Image credit: Andy Warhol, American (1928-1987) 'Pele,' 1977 Polacolor Type 108 4 ¼ x 3 3/8 inches Gift of The Andy Warhol Foundation for the Visual Arts, Inc., The Andy Warhol Photographic Legacy Program, CU Art Museum, University of Colorado at Boulder, 2008.2.39 © The Andy Warhol Foundation for the Visual Arts N 5/03/2011 10:00 AM 5/03/2011 07:00 PM Series 1085 18TH STREET Boulder CO Stages: 50 Years of Theatre at CU Celebrating the golden anniversary of the theater department through colorful photographs, costumes and props. N 5/05/2011 09:00 PM 5/05/2011 11:30 PM Series 1669 EUCLID AV Boulder CO http://www.colorado.edu/campusmap/map.html?bldg=UMC Commencement Commencement represents the official conferral of the earned academic degrees upon both undergraduate and graduate students. The University of Colorado at Boulder publicly acknowledges the students' significant educational achievements and accomplishments, and encourages the continued pursuit of education and personal realization. Commencement is the ceremonial fulfillment of the university's mission on the advancement of knowledge, and is the initiation of the students into the fellowship of this university. It is a time of celebration and reflection for students, families, friends, faculty, and staff - during which the university strives to create a memorable and meaningful occasion in a chapter of the lives of students and those who support them.<br /><br /> For more information about the ceremony, visit the Commencement <a href="http://www.colorado.edu/commencement/" target="_blank"> website</a>. The exhibition will also feature the more intimate Untitled (Mountain Landscape), circa 1920, which likely depicts Moraine Park.&#160;&#160; Born in Massachusetts, Charles Partridge Adams moved to Denver at the age of 18 and eventually became perhaps the most prolific and well known of the turn-of-the-century Colorado painters. Receiving artistic encouragement from Helen Henderson Chain, herself a pupil of George Inness, Adams shied away from the grandiose style employed by his contemporaries, preferring to accentuate the emotive in his landscapes and ushering in a long tradition of modernist landscape painting in the Rocky Mountain region. Adams Jr., sons of the late Charles Partridge Adams, CU Art Museum, University of Colorado at Boulder, 86.1825 Photo: J Wells © Regents of the University of Colorado / CU Art Museum N 5/06/2011 10:00 AM 5/06/2011 05:00 PM Series 1085 18TH STREET Boulder CO Highlights of the Collection: Selections from the Andy Warhol Photographic Legacy Program Gift <div>In 2008, the CU Art Museum received 156 photographs by Andy Warhol as a gift of the Andy Warhol Foundation for the Visual Arts as part of the Andy Warhol Photographic Legacy Program. The CU Art Museum will premier 112 of the gifted photographs which include Polaroids and gelatin silver prints featuring celebrities such as Martha Graham, Pel&#233;, and John Denver, as well as portraits of patrons, friends, and anonymous models. Included among the gifted gelatin silver prints are also landscapes and interior settings, both rural and urban, which reveal an aesthetic of the banal as well as the transcendental. The photographs provide valuable insight into the artist&#8217;s blurring of the distinction between &#8220;life&#8221; and &#8220;art&#8221; and his construct of &#8220;the celebrity.&#8221;&#160; The exhibition includes 80 Polaroids and 32 gelatin silver prints taken by the Pop-Art master. </div> <div>&#160;</div> <div> <u>Concurrent Exhibition:</u>&#160;&#160; <em>Warhol In Colorado</em>, an exhibition featuring screen prints, photographs, record album covers and other works by Andy Warhol, will be on view at The University of Denver&#8217;s Victoria H. Myhren Gallery from January 20 to March 13, 2011. Also included are 55 Polaroids and silver prints gifted to the university by the Andy Warhol Photographic Legacy Program in 2008.&#160; Details at <a href="http://myhrengallery.wordpress.com/our-namesake/">www.du.edu/art/myhrengallery </a><br /></div> <div> <br /> </div> <div>&#160;</div> <div>&#160;</div> Jennifer Conrad jennifer.conrad@colorado.edu Arts & Culture-Visual Arts,Arts and Sciences,CU Art Museum,Exhibits & Gallery Shows-Temporary / Visiting Exhibits Main Campus Visual Arts Complex CU Art Museum <li>Everyone</li> Free and open to the public Image credit: Andy Warhol, American (1928-1987) 'Pele,' 1977 Polacolor Type 108 4 ¼ x 3 3/8 inches Gift of The Andy Warhol Foundation for the Visual Arts, Inc., The Andy Warhol Photographic Legacy Program, CU Art Museum, University of Colorado at Boulder, 2008.2.39 © The Andy Warhol Foundation for the Visual Arts N 5/06/2011 10:00 AM 5/06/2011 05:00 PM Series 1085 18TH STREET Boulder CO Stages: 50 Years of Theatre at CU Celebrating the golden anniversary of the theater department through colorful photographs, costumes and props. Adams Jr., sons of the late Charles Partridge Adams, CU Art Museum, University of Colorado at Boulder, 86.1825 Photo: J Wells © Regents of the University of Colorado / CU Art Museum N 5/11/2011 10:00 AM 5/11/2011 05:00 PM Series 1085 18TH STREET Boulder CO Highlights of the Collection: Selections from the Andy Warhol Photographic Legacy Program Gift <div>In 2008, the CU Art Museum received 156 photographs by Andy Warhol as a gift of the Andy Warhol Foundation for the Visual Arts as part of the Andy Warhol Photographic Legacy Program. The CU Art Museum will premier 112 of the gifted photographs which include Polaroids and gelatin silver prints featuring celebrities such as Martha Graham, Pel&#233;, and John Denver, as well as portraits of patrons, friends, and anonymous models. Included among the gifted gelatin silver prints are also landscapes and interior settings, both rural and urban, which reveal an aesthetic of the banal as well as the transcendental. The photographs provide valuable insight into the artist&#8217;s blurring of the distinction between &#8220;life&#8221; and &#8220;art&#8221; and his construct of &#8220;the celebrity.&#8221;&#160; The exhibition includes 80 Polaroids and 32 gelatin silver prints taken by the Pop-Art master. </div> <div>&#160;</div> <div> <u>Concurrent Exhibition:</u>&#160;&#160; <em>Warhol In Colorado</em>, an exhibition featuring screen prints, photographs, record album covers and other works by Andy Warhol, will be on view at The University of Denver&#8217;s Victoria H. Myhren Gallery from January 20 to March 13, 2011. N 5/12/2011 10:00 AM 5/12/2011 05:00 PM Series 1085 18TH STREET Boulder CO Highlights of the Collection: Charles Partridge Adams Paintings The CU Art Museum presents two paintings by the noted Colorado landscape painter Charles Partridge Adams, including a never-before-shown, large-scale painting of Rocky Mountain scenery near Estes Park, titled Sunrise on the Mountains, circa 1920, recently conserved by the CU Art Museum, and gifted to the museum&#8217;s permanent collection by the artist&#8217;s sons. The exhibition will also feature the more intimate Untitled (Mountain Landscape), circa 1920, which likely depicts Moraine Park.&#160;&#160; Born in Massachusetts, Charles Partridge Adams moved to Denver at the age of 18 and eventually became perhaps the most prolific and well known of the turn-of-the-century Colorado painters. Receiving artistic encouragement from Helen Henderson Chain, herself a pupil of George Inness, Adams shied away from the grandiose style employed by his contemporaries, preferring to accentuate the emotive in his landscapes and ushering in a long tradition of modernist landscape painting in the Rocky Mountain region. Adams Jr., sons of the late Charles Partridge Adams, CU Art Museum, University of Colorado at Boulder, 86.1825 Photo: J Wells © Regents of the University of Colorado / CU Art Museum N 5/16/2011 10:00 AM 5/16/2011 05:00 PM Series 1085 18TH STREET Boulder CO Highlights of the Collection: Selections from the Andy Warhol Photographic Legacy Program Gift <div>In 2008, the CU Art Museum received 156 photographs by Andy Warhol as a gift of the Andy Warhol Foundation for the Visual Arts as part of the Andy Warhol Photographic Legacy Program. The CU Art Museum will premier 112 of the gifted photographs which include Polaroids and gelatin silver prints featuring celebrities such as Martha Graham, Pel&#233;, and John Denver, as well as portraits of patrons, friends, and anonymous models. Included among the gifted gelatin silver prints are also landscapes and interior settings, both rural and urban, which reveal an aesthetic of the banal as well as the transcendental. The photographs provide valuable insight into the artist&#8217;s blurring of the distinction between &#8220;life&#8221; and &#8220;art&#8221; and his construct of &#8220;the celebrity.&#8221;&#160; The exhibition includes 80 Polaroids and 32 gelatin silver prints taken by the Pop-Art master. </div> <div>&#160;</div> <div> <u>Concurrent Exhibition:</u>&#160;&#160; <em>Warhol In Colorado</em>, an exhibition featuring screen prints, photographs, record album covers and other works by Andy Warhol, will be on view at The University of Denver&#8217;s Victoria H. N 5/17/2011 10:00 AM 5/17/2011 07:00 PM Series 1085 18TH STREET Boulder CO Highlights of the Collection: Charles Partridge Adams Paintings The CU Art Museum presents two paintings by the noted Colorado landscape painter Charles Partridge Adams, including a never-before-shown, large-scale painting of Rocky Mountain scenery near Estes Park, titled Sunrise on the Mountains, circa 1920, recently conserved by the CU Art Museum, and gifted to the museum&#8217;s permanent collection by the artist&#8217;s sons. The exhibition will also feature the more intimate Untitled (Mountain Landscape), circa 1920, which likely depicts Moraine Park.&#160;&#160; Born in Massachusetts, Charles Partridge Adams moved to Denver at the age of 18 and eventually became perhaps the most prolific and well known of the turn-of-the-century Colorado painters. Receiving artistic encouragement from Helen Henderson Chain, herself a pupil of George Inness, Adams shied away from the grandiose style employed by his contemporaries, preferring to accentuate the emotive in his landscapes and ushering in a long tradition of modernist landscape painting in the Rocky Mountain region.
